", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Archery_at_the_Summer_Olympics"}
{"title_page": "Satyricon (nightclub)", "text_new": "{{Infobox Venue\n| name                =  Satyricon \n| native_name         = \n| native_name_lang    = \n| logo_image          = Satyricon Club Logo.jpg\n| logo_size           =\n| logo_alt            =\n| logo_caption        =\n| image               = Satyricon2007.png\n| image_alt           = \n| image_caption       = Satyricon in 2007\n| pushpin_map            = Portland\n| pushpin_mapsize        = 220px\n| former_names        = Marlena's Tavern\n| building_type       = \n| location            = \n| address             = 125 N.W. Sixth Avenue<br>[[Portland, Oregon|Portland]], [[Oregon]], U.S.\n| coordinates         = {{coord| 45.524209 | -122.676773}}\n| yearsactive=1983{{en dash}}2003; 2006{{en dash}}2010\n| opened   = March 1984\n| inauguration_date   = \n| relocated_date      = \n| renovation_date     =  \n| closed        = November 1, 2010<ref name=long/>\n| demolished   = July 2011\n| seating_capacity    = 400<ref>{{cite web|url=http://psuvanguard.com/the-return-of-satyricon/|work=The Vanguard|title=The return of the Satyricon|date=September 11, 2006|author=Johnson, Ed|accessdate=November 24, 2015}}</ref>\n| references          = \n| footnotes           =\n}}\n\n'''Satyricon''' was a [[nightclub]] in the [[Old Town Chinatown, Portland, Oregon|Old Town]] neighborhood of [[Portland, Oregon]], [[United States]] that operated from 1984 to 2010. It was the longest-running punk venue in the western United States,<ref name=ithink/> and has been referred to by some journalists and historians as the \"[[CBGB]] of the West Coast.\"<ref name=wweek/><ref>{{cite book|title=Walking Portland: 30 Tours of Stumptown's Funky Neighborhoods, Historic Landmarks, Park Trails, Farmers Markets, and Brewpubs  |page=4|author=Ohlsen, Becky|year=2013|publisher=Wilderness Press|isbn= 978-0-899-97682-2}}</ref>\n\nLocated in a building that had served as a [[Stable|horse stable]] in the early 1900s, the club's owner, George Touhouliotis, founded Satyricon after acquiring a tavern that had operated in the building. Touhouliotis reshaped the tavern into a nightclub, and named it after the 1969 [[Federico Fellini]] [[Fellini Satyricon|film of the same name]]. Satyricon became a prominent music venue in the city, and hosted various local and touring [[punk rock|punk]] and [[alternative rock]] bands throughout the 1980s and 1990s.\n\nIn May 2003, the club abruptly closed, after which it was acquired by new owners and reopened as an all-ages venue in 2006. It officially closed in November 2010, and the building in which it was located was demolished in July 2011. The club was the subject of a 2013 documentary titled ''Satyricon: Madness and Glory''.\n\n==History==\n===Background===\nThe Satyricon, located at 125 N.W. Sixth Avenue, was formerly Marlena's Tavern, \"a dark, narrow barroom on a seedy stretch.\"<ref name=\"ana\"/> Prior to its establishment as a bar and restaurant, the building had served as a [[horse stable]] in the early 20th century before being converted into a tavern.<ref name=\"notorious\"/>\n\nSatyricon was founded by George Touhouliotis, a former [[taxi]] driver who acquired Marlena's Tavern in 1983.<ref name=notorious/> Upon taking ownership, Touhouliotis re-conceived the location as a nightclub that would offer live music.<ref name=notorious/> He named the club '''Satyricon''' after the 1969 [[Federico Fellini]] [[Fellini Satyricon|film of the same name]].<ref name=wweek/> At the time, the surrounding [[Old Town Chinatown, Portland, Oregon|Old Town Chinatown]] neighborhood had a seedy and dangerous reputation.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.vice.com/read/portlands-iconic-old-town-is-overflowing-with-human-shit|work=Vice|title=Portland's Iconic Old Town Chinatown Is Overflowing with Human Shit|author=Sernoffsky, Evan|date=March 19, 2014|accessdate=November 23, 2015}}</ref> The block was characterized as Portland's [[skid row]],{{sfn|Trombold|Donahue|2017|p=402}} \"a real shithole of a neighborhood\" with \"open drug dealing, fights, knives, [and] guns.\"{{sfn|Schultz|2015|p=5}} Local historian SP Clarke recalled that \"A mere attempt to walk the sidewalks ... required a helmet and full body armor.\"{{sfn|Schultz|2015|p=5}}\n\n===Early years and heyday===\n====1980s====\n{{quotebox|align=left|bgcolor=lavender|width=25%|quote=In 1984, there was no [[Pearl District, Portland, Oregon|Pearl District]], no River District, no [[Lan Su Chinese Garden|Chinese Garden]], no [[MAX Light Rail|MAX]]. Instead of a sedate old folks' home, Satyricon's neighbors included a shady grocery store (later bombed) and a corner dive bar longtime Portlanders still remember with a shiver. Instead of Fellini, dolled-up rockers and living ghosts from Old Town's street scene jostled around a gyros counter oh-so-accurately named Eat or Die.|source=Journalist Zach Dundas on the club's location in the 1980s<ref name=notorious/>}}\n\nSatyricon opened in March 1984,{{efn|Per a ''Willamette Week'' article dated March 12, 1984, Satyricon had been in its second week of business, indicating the official opening date would have been some time in early March 1984.<ref name=notorious>{{cite web|url=http://www.wweek.com/portland/article-2032-notorious.html|work=Willamette Week|title=Notorious|date=May 13, 2003|author=Dundas, Zach|accessdate=May 15, 2018}}</ref>}} and attracted a wide array of musical groups, as the club's booking agent made \"no stylistic or hierarchical\" distinction among the musical acts.<ref name=tl>{{cite web|work=Two Louies Magazine|url=http://www.twolouiesmagazine.com/history/history-of-portland-rock-3/|author=Clarke, SP|title=History of Portland Rock III: The Mid 80s|accessdate=May 17, 2018|date=2011}}</ref> Local punk bands the [[Wipers]] and [[Poison Idea]] became notable regular acts at the club,<ref name=\"ana\">{{cite web|url=http://oregonmusicnews.com/2010/10/20/satyricon-says-farewell-for-the-last-time/|work=Oregon Music News|title=Satyricon says farewell for the last time|author=Ammann, Ana|date=October 20, 2010|accessdate=September 11, 2012}}</ref><ref name=wweek>{{cite news| url = http://www.wweek.com/story.php?story=400 | title = Music & Nightlife: Hiss and Vinegar\u2014Satyricon Morphs Into Moody's | author = Willamette Week Music Staff | work = Willamette Week| date = June 11, 2003| accessdate = October 24, 2010}}</ref> as well as various [[underground music|underground]] musicians.{{sfn|Oregon Liquor Control Commission|1986|p=14}} According to public documents regarding the business's liquor control license, Satyricon opened at 8 p.m. each night, and offered \"live music and dancing\" from 10 p.m. until around 2:30&nbsp;a.m.{{sfn|Oregon Liquor Control Commission|1986|p=4}} Additionally, the club hosted [[open mic]] nights, [[poetry reading]]s, and [[performance art]] exhibitions.<ref name=\"alternate\"/><ref name=mm>{{cite journal|work=Multnomah Magazine|pages=4\u20136|url=http://www.ochcom.org/pdf/DavidHorowitzA.pdf|title=George Touhouliotis: The Passion Behind Satyricon|date=December 1984|series=Excerpt|accessdate=May 17, 2018|format=PDF}}</ref>\n\nOn September 20, 1985, Satyricon began offering food,{{sfn|Oregon Liquor Control Commission|1986|p=6}} which included a [[souvlaki]] take-out window called Eat or Die.<ref name=notorious/> By 1985, the club was selling around $7,000 of alcoholic beverages per month, and around $3,000 in food, with 20% of all food orders occurring through the take-out window.{{sfn|Oregon Liquor Control Commission|1986|p=6}} Owner Touhoulitis petitioned for the [[Oregon Liquor Control Commission]] (OLCC) to allow for relaxations on allowing minors into the club's bandstand area between March 1984 and July 1985,{{sfn|Oregon Liquor Control Commission|1986|p=18}} but multiple incidents in which [[minor (law)|minors]] infiltrated the bar led the OLCC to determine that \"the premises [are] not suitable for increased access by minors.\"{{sfn|Oregon Liquor Control Commission|1986|p=14}} This largely had to do with the club's layout, which maintained little division between the bandstand and the bar.{{sfn|Oregon Liquor Control Commission|1986|pages=13\u201318}} The interior of the building was described by journalists as such:\n\n{{quote|As you step up to the long, obsidian-black bar, you may notice the [[Buddharupa|Buddha]] that presides from behind the bar, the sensual art above, and stars on the ceiling. Explore a bit more and you'll find graffiti on the tables, an open-staged DJ booth, black & white checkered floors, and the infamous Round-table, in a corner, with a [[pentagram]] etched into it. Now, it's time that we enter the inner sanctum, the stage area. Plastered with hundreds of band stickers, that would take someone days to take in. Like a museum of modern art, you see the history dating back to its unveiling in 1983. The stage itself is comfortable, like an old basement rehearsal space with a high ceiling.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.inmusicwetrust.com/articles/52f05.html|work=In Music We Trust|title=Nightclub Review: The Satyricon|author1=Black, Jett |author2=V., Marty |date=September 2002|issue=52|accessdate=November 22, 2015}}</ref>}}\n[[File:Satyricon_c._January_1989.jpg|thumb|right|upright=1|[[Courtney Love]] {{small|(right)}} and other patrons attending an event at Satyricon {{circa}} 1989]]\n\nIn the mid-1980s, the club was frequented by local residents such as poet [[Walt Curtis]]<ref name=hughley/> and [[Courtney Love]], the latter of whom met friend and bandmate [[Kat Bjelland]] there in 1984<ref name=ithink>{{cite web|url=http://www.wweek.com/portland/article-12560-i_think_i_was_there.html|work=Willamette Week|title=I Think I Was There: An oral history of the Satyricon|author1=Jarman, Casey |author2=Mannheimer, Michael |author3=Horton, Jay |date=October 27, 2010|accessdate=September 11, 2012}}</ref><ref name=\"alternate\">{{cite web|url=http://www.wweek.com/portland/blog-30813-an_(alternate)_oral_history_of_satyricon.html|work=Willamette Week|title=An (Alternate) Oral History of the Satyricon|date=October 16, 2013|author=Horton, Jay|accessdate=November 22, 2015}}</ref> through [[The Miracle Workers]]' frontman Gerry Mohr.{{sfn|Evans|1994|p=65}} The club is also notable for being the place where Love first crossed paths with her future husband, [[Nirvana (band)|Nirvana]] frontman [[Kurt Cobain]].  In a 2010 interview, she claimed she met Cobain there in 1988 at a [[Dharma Bums (band)|Dharma Bums]] concert where she was reading [[spoken word]] poetry,<ref>{{cite episode|network=Fuse|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=fgqt0ofwE3g|series=On The Record|title=Interview with Courtney Love|date=May 10, 2010|accessdate=May 14, 2018}}</ref> although other accounts state that the two met in January 1989 or 1990<ref name=beast>{{cite web|url=http://www.thedailybeast.com/articles/2014/03/04/the-moment-kurt-cobain-met-courtney-love.html|work=[[The Daily Beast]]|title=The Moment Kurt Cobain Met Courtney Love|date=April 5, 2014|author=Cross, Charles|accessdate=October 29, 2014|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170609113438/http://www.thedailybeast.com/the-moment-kurt-cobain-met-courtney-love|archivedate=June 9, 2017}}</ref> when Nirvana was playing at the club,{{sfn|Green|2003|pages=69\u201370}} and that they playfully wrestled in front of a [[jukebox]] that night.<ref name=beast/> [[Mark Arm]] of [[Mudhoney]] would later claim the story to be apocryphal, and that two in fact met while Mudhoney was touring with Love's band [[Hole (band)|Hole]] in Europe in 1991.{{sfn|Yarm|2011|p=256}} In a 2015 interview, Love clarified: \"It was at the Satyricon ... I sometimes lie and say which bands were playing but I actually don't remember. But Nirvana was obviously playing. He was cute, he was attractive, and he was funny ... Everyone always writes that the song that was playing [on the jukebox] was [[Living Colour]], but that wasn't it. It was \"Dear Friend\" by Flying Color.<ref>{{cite web|work=[[V (American magazine)|V]]|title=Courtney Love on ''Kurt Cobain: Montage of Heck''|url=https://www.vmagazine.com/site/content/4111/courtney-love-on-kurt-cobain-montage-of-heck|date=May 2015|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150905212809/https://www.vmagazine.com/site/content/4111/courtney-love-on-kurt-cobain-montage-of-heck|archivedate=September 5, 2015|author=Sandberg, Patrik}}</ref>\n\nCommenting on the various stories and lore surrounding the club, journalist Zach Dundas wrote: \"The written record of the club's existence{{en dash}}which can amount to no more than 1 percent of the Whole Truth{{en dash}}is a florid tale of excess, controversy, creative chaos. And, yes, artistic greatness.\"<ref name=notorious/>\n\n====1990s====\nIn 1990, a [[charity record|benefit]] [[LP record]] was put out for the club called \"''Satyricon ... the Album''\".  It included tracks from local punk acts such as Poison Idea, Dharma Bums and Napalm Beach.<ref name=zenorecords>{{cite web\n | url = http://zenorecords.com/product/satyricon-the-album-cdr/\n | title = Satyricon The Album (CDR)\n | work = zenorecords\n | accessdate = April 24, 2016\n}}</ref> Beginning in the early 1990s, Satyricon became a frequent host to [[grunge]] bands,<ref name=samson>{{cite book|title=Frommer's Seattle and Portland, '94-'95|publisher=Prentice Hall Travel|year=1994|p=[https://archive.org/details/frommerscomprehe00sams/page/242 242]|author=Samson, Karl|isbn=978-0-671-86659-4|url=https://archive.org/details/frommerscomprehe00sams/page/242}}</ref> including Nirvana,<ref>{{cite web|work=Spin|url=https://www.spin.com/2015/01/nirvana-unheard-concert-satyricon-dale-crover/|date=January 12, 2015|accessdate=May 16, 2018|title=Listen to a 25-Year-Old Nirvana Concert Bootleg Nobody's Ever Heard Before|author=Grebey, James}}</ref> [[Soundgarden]], [[Pearl Jam]], and Mudhoney, among others.<ref name=ithink/><ref name=hughley/> In  1993, Satyricon opened its own restaurant called ''Fellini'', a nod to the club's namesake.<ref name=wweek/>\n\n[[Dave Grohl]] played his first show with his post-Nirvana outfit [[Foo Fighters]] (after [[Death of Kurt Cobain|Cobain's suicide]]) at Satyricon.<ref>{{cite journal|work=Spin|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Z1BJTsbRdMEC&pg=PA44&dq=foo+fighters+satyricon&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjk5MftrovbAhWnxlQKHao7BToQ6AEIKTAA#v=onepage&q=foo%20fighters%20satyricon&f=false|title=Live!: Foo Fighters|p=44|date=June 1995|via=Google Books|volume=11|number=3|issn=0886-3032}} {{free access}}</ref> Other events, besides notable concerts, include a number of incidents involving notable people (including Courtney Love passing out) and a police riot in 1990.<ref name=notorious/>\n\n===Renovation and closure===\n[[File:F***ed Up (live at Satyricon, 2008).jpg|thumb|right|upright=1|[[Fucked Up]] performing at Satyricon, 2008]]\nIn May 2003, Satyricon abruptly closed and was slated to be taken over by the owners of another (former) club in town, Moody's.<ref name=hughley/> It reopened as an all-ages club in August 2006 under the management of the owners of the Loveland, an all-ages venue in Portland.<ref name=hughley>{{cite web\n | url = http://www.oregonlive.com/music/index.ssf/2010/10/post_19.html\n | title = Portland nightclub Satyricon says farewell with series of reunion shows\n | author = Marty Hughley\n | date = October 18, 2010\n | work = The Oregonian\n | accessdate = October 24, 2010\n}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wweek.com/portland/article-5915-local_news_reviews.html|work=Willamette Week|date=August 9, 2006|accessdate=September 11, 2012|title=Legendary Portland rock club Satyricon to reopen; Loveland to fade away}}</ref><ref>{{cite web\n | url = http://www.wweek.com/portland/blog-20441-satyricon_to_close_%28forever%29_in_october.html\n | title = Satyricon to Close (Forever) in October\n | author = Jarman, Casey\n | date =  August 3, 2010\n | work = Willamette Week\n | accessdate = February 4, 2012\n}}</ref> Mild renovations were undertaken, though a review of the club upon its reopening noted: \"The club looks the same ... eerily so. Same bar stools, same black paint. At the same time, it looks unfinished, like someone decided to remodel, ripped up a few boards and then totally slacked off.\"<ref>{{cite web|work=Portland Tribune|url=http://portlandtribune.com/component/content/article?id=102930|author=DiStefano, Anne Marie|date=September 21, 2006|accessdate=May 15, 2018|title=Satyricon lifts the curtain for next generation of fans}}</ref>\n\nIn October 2010, Ben Munat, the Satyricon's booking agent, organized thirteen \"''Farewell Satyricon Shows''\" for that month.<ref name=hughley/><ref>{{cite web|work=Portland Mercury|url=https://www.portlandmercury.com/endhits/archives/2010/08/06/the-end-of-satyricon-an-interview-with-the-fabled-clubs-co-ownerbooker-jeff-urquhart|title=The End of Satyricon: An Interview with the Fabled Club's Co-Owner/Booker, Jeff Urquhart|date=August 6, 2010|author=Caraeff, Ezra Ace|accessdate=May 9, 2018}}</ref> Bands included Big Daddy Meat Straw, the [[Dandy Warhols]] (with original drummer Eric Hedford, playing songs from first two albums with some original guitars), Pond, Poison Idea, and Napalm Beach,<ref name=Vondersmith/> with the final concert taking place on October 31, 2010.<ref name=long/> Commenting on the club's closure, owner Touhouliotis said: \"I had gotten tired. A place like that runs on creativity and energy; it's not automatic. And by the late '90s, the turn of the millennium, my energy wasn't there.\"<ref name=hughley/>\n\n===Demolition and aftermath===\nDemolition of the building began in July 2011,<ref>{{cite web|author=Hottle, Molly|date=July 27, 2011|url=http://www.oregonlive.com/portland/index.ssf/2011/07/demolition_begins_on_building.html|title=Demolition begins on building that once housed Satyricon nightclub|work=The Oregonian|accessdate=November 27, 2011}}</ref> after which many pieces of furniture, memorabilia, and parts of the building were \"unceremoniously given away to anyone interested.\"<ref name=long/> The urinal trough in the men's restroom was reportedly acquired by a [[tulip]] farm in [[Gresham, Oregon|Gresham]].<ref name=long/> The marquee above the club's entrance was believed to have been either stolen or destroyed in the demolition process, as it remained unaccounted for.<ref name=long>{{cite web|url=http://www.wweek.com/uncategorized/2017/05/19/the-long-lost-satyricon-sign-resurfaces-at-the-dandy-warhols-old-portland-wine-bar/|work=Willamette Week|title=The Long-Lost Satyricon Sign Resurfaces at the Dandy Warhols' Old Portland Wine Bar|author=Horton, Jay|date=May 19, 2017|accessdate=May 16, 2018}}</ref> In 2017, [[Courtney Taylor-Taylor]], frontman of the Dandy Warhols, reported that he had found the marquee, which he had installed at The Old Portland, a wine bar he opened in 2016.<ref name=long/> The location of the original building is now home to the nonprofit MacDonald Center service center and studio apartments to serve low-income residents.<ref name=Vondersmith>{{cite web | url = http://portlandtribune.com/component/content/article?id=37020\n | title = Satyricon refuses to go quietly\n | author = Vondersmith, Jason\n | date =  September 29, 2010\n | work = Portland Tribune\n | accessdate = April 24, 2016\n}}</ref>\n\n==In popular culture==\nThe club was used as a filming location for [[Gus Van Sant]]'s 1985 film, ''[[Mala Noche]]''.<ref name=\"alternate\"/> In 2013, after its demolition, a documentary about the club, ''Satyricon: Madness and Glory'', was released.<ref name=doc>{{cite web|work=[[KPTV]]|url=http://www.kptv.com/story/23706685/satyricon-movie-remembers-infamous-portland-nightclub|title=Satyricon movie remembers infamous Portland nightclub|date=October 16, 2013|author=FOX 12 Staff|accessdate=May 16, 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Notable bands==\nThe following are documented bands that notably performed at Satyricon:{{citation needed|date=May 2018}}<ref name=\"hughley\"/><ref name=\"alternate\"/><ref name=\"Martin James\"/><ref name=\"Pearl Jam venues\"/><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.setlist.fm/venue/satyricon-portland-or-usa-2bd6d472.html?page=27 |title=Satyricon Portland Concert Setlists |work=setlist.fm |accessdate=April 24, 2016}}</ref>\n \n{{columns-list|colwidth=30em|\n*[[90 Proof]]\n*[[The Acc\u00fcsed]]\n*[[All Out (band)|All Out]]\n*[[Amy Denio]]\n*[[Armored Saint]]\n*[[Bevis Frond]]\n*[[Bodybag]]\n*[[Camper Van Beethoven]]\n*[[Cannibal Corpse]]\n*[[Chevelle (band)|Chevelle]]\n*[[Chrome Dog with Bif Naked]]\n*[[Clever Cadavers]]\n*The Confidentials\n*[[The Dandy Warhols]]\n*[[The Dead Milkmen]]\n*[[Dead Moon]]\n*[[Deli Creeps]]\n*[[The Delinquents (band)|The Delinquents]]\n*[[Dharma Bums]]\n*[[Elliott Smith]]<ref>https://www.setlist.fm/setlist/elliott-smith/1999/satyricon-portland-or-7bdf8e0c.html</ref>\n*[[Everclear (band)|Everclear]]\n* [[Final Warning]]\n*[[The Flaming Lips]]\n*[[Foo Fighters]]\n*[[GWAR]]\n*[[Green Day]]\n*[[Green River (band)|Green River]]\n*[[Greg Sage (band)|Greg Sage]]\n*[[Heatmiser]]\n*Hitting Birth\n*The Jackals\n*The Jimmies\n*[[Juliana Hatfield]]\n*[[The Hetros]]\n*[[King Black Acid (band)|King Black Acid]]\n*[[L7 (band)|L7]]\n*[[Local H]]\n*[[Lockjaw (band)|Lockjaw]]\n*[[Meat Puppets]]\n*[[Melvins]]\n*[[The Mentors]]\n*[[Mojo Nixon]]\n*[[Mother Love Bone]]\n*[[Mudhoney]]\n*[[Naked Violence]]\n*[[Napalm Beach]]\n*[[Nightcaps (band)|Nightcaps]]\n*[[Nirvana (band)|Nirvana]]\n*[[Oasis (band)|Oasis]]\n*[[Obituaries (band)|The Obituaries]]\n*[[Pavement (band)|Pavement]]\n*[[Pearl Jam]]\n*[[Poison Idea]]\n*[[Pond (American band)|Pond]]\n*[[Portugal. The Man]]\n*[[The Presidents of the United States of America (band)|The Presidents of the United States of America]]\n*[[Queens of the Stone Age]]\n*[[Richmond Fontaine]]\n*[[The Reeds Mill Investigation]]\n*[[Saint Vitus (band)|Saint Vitus]]\n*[[Sic Fucks]]\n*[[Sleater-Kinney]]\n*[[Sloppy Seconds]]\n*[[Snowbird (band)|Snowbird]]\n*[[Soul Asylum]]\n*[[Spastic Blur]]\n*[[Speed Weenie]]\n*[[Spoon (band)|Spoon]]\n*[[Sweaty Nipples]]\n*[[Tattooed Corpse]]\n*[[Voivod (band)|Voivod]]\n*[[Ween (band)|Ween]]\n*[[Wehrmacht]]\n*[[White Zombie (band)|White Zombie]]\n*[[Wipers]]\n*[[Wreck-Creation]]\n*[[Wretched Death]]\n*[[Zipgun]]}}\n\n== See also ==\n* [[X-Ray Cafe]]\n* [[La Luna (Portland, Oregon)|La Luna]]\n*[[Music of Oregon]]\n\n==Notes==\n{{noteslist}}\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==Works cited==\n*{{cite book|last=Evans|first=Liz|title=Women, Sex and Rock'n'roll: In Their Own Words|year=1994|publisher=Pandora|isbn=978-0-044-40900-7|oclc=494693178|ref=harv|url=https://archive.org/details/womensexrocknrol0000unse}}\n*{{cite book|last=Green|first=Joey|title=How They Met: Fateful Encounters of Famous Lovebirds, Rivals, Partners in Crime|publisher=Black Dog Publishing|year=2003|isbn=978-1-4223-6673-8|ref=harv|oclc=52621239}}\n*{{cite web|url=http://www.oregon.gov/olcc/docs/final_orders/final_orders_1986/satyricon_85_l_032.pdf|author=Oregon Liquor Control Commission (OLCC)|work=Oregon Liquor Control Commission|title=Final Order: Satyricon|ref={{sfnref|Oregon Liquor Control Commission|1986}}|format=PDF|publisher=State of Oregon|year=1986}}\n*{{cite book|last=Schultz|first=William Todd|year=2015|title=Torment Saint: The Life of Elliott Smith|publisher=Bloomsbury USA|ref=harv|isbn= 978-1-620-40784-4}}\n*{{cite book|last1=Trombold|first1=John|last2=Donahue|first2=Peter, eds.|year=2017|title=Reading Portland: The City in Prose|publisher=University of Washington Press|ref=harv|isbn=978-0-295-99760-5}}\n*{{cite book|last=Yarm|first=Mark|title=Everybody Loves Our Town: An Oral History of Grunge|isbn=978-0-307-46444-6|location=New York|publisher=Three Rivers Press|year=2011|ref=harv|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=z-44p7V2TrUC&printsec=frontcover|oclc=935232799}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category|Satyricon (nightclub)}}\n*[https://www.setlist.fm/venue/satyricon-portland-or-usa-2bd6d472.html List of concerts] at Satyricon via Setlist.fm\n\n{{Old Town Chinatown, Portland, Oregon}}\n{{coord| 45.524209 | -122.676773 | type:landmark_region:US-OR_source:googlemaps_dim:30 | display=title}}<!-- geocoded \"125 Northwest 6th Avenue, Portland, Oregon\" -->\n\n[[Category:Defunct nightclubs in Portland, Oregon]]\n[[Category:Former music venues in the United States]]\n[[Category:Demolished music venues in the United States]]\n[[Category:Demolished buildings and structures in Portland, Oregon]]\n[[Category:Old Town Chinatown, Portland, Oregon]]\n[[Category:1984 establishments in Oregon]]\n[[Category:2010 disestablishments in Oregon]]\n[[Category:Northwest Portland, Oregon]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox Venue\n| name                =  Satyricon \n| native_name         = \n| native_name_lang    = \n| logo_image          = Satyricon Club Logo.jpg\n| logo_size           =\n| logo_alt            =\n| logo_caption        =\n| image               = Satyricon2007.png\n| image_alt           = \n| image_caption       = Satyricon in 2007\n| pushpin_map            = Portland\n| pushpin_mapsize        = 220px\n| former_names        = Marlena's Tavern\n| building_type       = \n| location            = \n| address             = 125 N.W. Sixth Avenue<br>[[Portland, Oregon|Portland]], [[Oregon]], U.S.\n| coordinates         = {{coord| 45.524209 | -122.676773}}\n| yearsactive=1983{{en dash}}2003; 2006{{en dash}}2010\n| opened   = March 1984\n| inauguration_date   = \n| relocated_date      = \n| renovation_date     =  \n| closed        = November 1, 2010<ref name=long/>\n| demolished   = July 2011\n| seating_capacity    = 400<ref>{{cite web|url=http://psuvanguard.com/the-return-of-satyricon/|work=The Vanguard|title=The return of the Satyricon|date=September 11, 2006|author=Johnson, Ed|accessdate=November 24, 2015}}</ref>\n| references          = \n| footnotes           =\n}}\n\n'''Satyricon''' was a [[nightclub]] in the [[Old Town Chinatown, Portland, Oregon|Old Town]] neighborhood of [[Portland, Oregon]], [[United States]] that operated from 1984 to 2010. It was the longest-running punk venue in the western United States,<ref name=ithink/> and has been referred to by some journalists and historians as the \"[[CBGB]] of the West Coast.\"<ref name=wweek/><ref>{{cite book|title=Walking Portland: 30 Tours of Stumptown's Funky Neighborhoods, Historic Landmarks, Park Trails, Farmers Markets, and Brewpubs  |page=4|author=Ohlsen, Becky|year=2013|publisher=Wilderness Press|isbn= 978-0-899-97682-2}}</ref>\n\nLocated in a building that had served as a [[Stable|horse stable]] in the early 1900s, the club's owner, George Touhouliotis, founded Satyricon after acquiring a tavern that had operated in the building. Touhouliotis reshaped the tavern into a nightclub, and named it after the 1969 [[Federico Fellini]] [[Fellini Satyricon|film of the same name]]. Satyricon became a prominent music venue in the city, and hosted various local and touring [[punk rock|punk]] and [[alternative rock]] bands throughout the 1980s and 1990s.\n\nIn May 2003, the club abruptly closed, after which it was acquired by new owners and reopened as an all-ages venue in 2006. It officially closed in November 2010, and the building in which it was located was demolished in July 2011. The club was the subject of a 2013 documentary titled ''Satyricon: Madness and Glory''.\n\n==History==\n===Background===\nThe Satyricon, located at 125 N.W. Sixth Avenue, was formerly Marlena's Tavern, \"a dark, narrow barroom on a seedy stretch.\"<ref name=\"ana\"/> Prior to its establishment as a bar and restaurant, the building had served as a [[horse stable]] in the early 20th century before being converted into a tavern.<ref name=\"notorious\"/>\n\nSatyricon was founded by George Touhouliotis, a former [[taxi]] driver who acquired Marlena's Tavern in 1983.<ref name=notorious/> Upon taking ownership, Touhouliotis re-conceived the location as a nightclub that would offer live music.<ref name=notorious/> He named the club '''Satyricon''' after the 1969 [[Federico Fellini]] [[Fellini Satyricon|film of the same name]].<ref name=wweek/> At the time, the surrounding [[Old Town Chinatown, Portland, Oregon|Old Town Chinatown]] neighborhood had a seedy and dangerous reputation.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.vice.com/read/portlands-iconic-old-town-is-overflowing-with-human-shit|work=Vice|title=Portland's Iconic Old Town Chinatown Is Overflowing with Human Shit|author=Sernoffsky, Evan|date=March 19, 2014|accessdate=November 23, 2015}}</ref> The block was characterized as Portland's [[skid row]],{{sfn|Trombold|Donahue|2017|p=402}} \"a real shithole of a neighborhood\" with \"open drug dealing, fights, knives, [and] guns.\"{{sfn|Schultz|2015|p=5}} Local historian SP Clarke recalled that \"A mere attempt to walk the sidewalks ... required a helmet and full body armor.\"{{sfn|Schultz|2015|p=5}}\n\n===Early years and heyday===\n====1980s====\n{{quotebox|align=left|bgcolor=lavender|width=25%|quote=In 1984, there was no [[Pearl District, Portland, Oregon|Pearl District]], no River District, no [[Lan Su Chinese Garden|Chinese Garden]], no [[MAX Light Rail|MAX]]. Instead of a sedate old folks' home, Satyricon's neighbors included a shady grocery store (later bombed) and a corner dive bar longtime Portlanders still remember with a shiver. Instead of Fellini, dolled-up rockers and living ghosts from Old Town's street scene jostled around a gyros counter oh-so-accurately named Eat or Die.|source=Journalist Zach Dundas on the club's location in the 1980s<ref name=notorious/>}}\n\nSatyricon opened in March 1984,{{efn|Per a ''Willamette Week'' article dated March 12, 1984, Satyricon had been in its second week of business, indicating the official opening date would have been some time in early March 1984.<ref name=notorious>{{cite web|url=http://www.wweek.com/portland/article-2032-notorious.html|work=Willamette Week|title=Notorious|date=May 13, 2003|author=Dundas, Zach|accessdate=May 15, 2018}}</ref>}} and attracted a wide array of musical groups, as the club's booking agent made \"no stylistic or hierarchical\" distinction among the musical acts.<ref name=tl>{{cite web|work=Two Louies Magazine|url=http://www.twolouiesmagazine.com/history/history-of-portland-rock-3/|author=Clarke, SP|title=History of Portland Rock III: The Mid 80s|accessdate=May 17, 2018|date=2011}}</ref> Local punk bands the [[Wipers]] and [[Poison Idea]] became notable regular acts at the club,<ref name=\"ana\">{{cite web|url=http://oregonmusicnews.com/2010/10/20/satyricon-says-farewell-for-the-last-time/|work=Oregon Music News|title=Satyricon says farewell for the last time|author=Ammann, Ana|date=October 20, 2010|accessdate=September 11, 2012}}</ref><ref name=wweek>{{cite news| url = http://www.wweek.com/story.php?story=400 | title = Music & Nightlife: Hiss and Vinegar\u2014Satyricon Morphs Into Moody's | author = Willamette Week Music Staff | work = Willamette Week| date = June 11, 2003| accessdate = October 24, 2010}}</ref> as well as various [[underground music|underground]] musicians.{{sfn|Oregon Liquor Control Commission|1986|p=14}} According to public documents regarding the business's liquor control license, Satyricon opened at 8 p.m. each night, and offered \"live music and dancing\" from 10 p.m. until around 2:30&nbsp;a.m.{{sfn|Oregon Liquor Control Commission|1986|p=4}} Additionally, the club hosted [[open mic]] nights, [[poetry reading]]s, and [[performance art]] exhibitions.<ref name=\"alternate\"/><ref name=mm>{{cite journal|work=Multnomah Magazine|pages=4\u20136|url=http://www.ochcom.org/pdf/DavidHorowitzA.pdf|title=George Touhouliotis: The Passion Behind Satyricon|date=December 1984|series=Excerpt|accessdate=May 17, 2018|format=PDF}}</ref>\n\nOn September 20, 1985, Satyricon began offering food,{{sfn|Oregon Liquor Control Commission|1986|p=6}} which included a [[souvlaki]] take-out window called Eat or Die.<ref name=notorious/> By 1985, the club was selling around $7,000 of alcoholic beverages per month, and around $3,000 in food, with 20% of all food orders occurring through the take-out window.{{sfn|Oregon Liquor Control Commission|1986|p=6}} Owner Touhoulitis petitioned for the [[Oregon Liquor Control Commission]] (OLCC) to allow for relaxations on allowing minors into the club's bandstand area between March 1984 and July 1985,{{sfn|Oregon Liquor Control Commission|1986|p=18}} but multiple incidents in which [[minor (law)|minors]] infiltrated the bar led the OLCC to determine that \"the premises [are] not suitable for increased access by minors.\"{{sfn|Oregon Liquor Control Commission|1986|p=14}} This largely had to do with the club's layout, which maintained little division between the bandstand and the bar.{{sfn|Oregon Liquor Control Commission|1986|pages=13\u201318}} The interior of the building was described by journalists as such:\n\n{{quote|As you step up to the long, obsidian-black bar, you may notice the [[Buddharupa|Buddha]] that presides from behind the bar, the sensual art above, and stars on the ceiling. Explore a bit more and you'll find graffiti on the tables, an open-staged DJ booth, black & white checkered floors, and the infamous Round-table, in a corner, with a [[pentagram]] etched into it. Now, it's time that we enter the inner sanctum, the stage area. Plastered with hundreds of band stickers, that would take someone days to take in. Like a museum of modern art, you see the history dating back to its unveiling in 1983. The stage itself is comfortable, like an old basement rehearsal space with a high ceiling.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.inmusicwetrust.com/articles/52f05.html|work=In Music We Trust|title=Nightclub Review: The Satyricon|author1=Black, Jett |author2=V., Marty |date=September 2002|issue=52|accessdate=November 22, 2015}}</ref>}}\n[[File:Satyricon_c._January_1989.jpg|thumb|right|upright=1|[[Courtney Love]] {{small|(right)}} and other patrons attending an event at Satyricon {{circa}} 1989]]\n\nIn the mid-1980s, the club was frequented by local residents such as poet [[Walt Curtis]]<ref name=hughley/> and [[Courtney Love]], the latter of whom met friend and bandmate [[Kat Bjelland]] there in 1984<ref name=ithink>{{cite web|url=http://www.wweek.com/portland/article-12560-i_think_i_was_there.html|work=Willamette Week|title=I Think I Was There: An oral history of the Satyricon|author1=Jarman, Casey |author2=Mannheimer, Michael |author3=Horton, Jay |date=October 27, 2010|accessdate=September 11, 2012}}</ref><ref name=\"alternate\">{{cite web|url=http://www.wweek.com/portland/blog-30813-an_(alternate)_oral_history_of_satyricon.html|work=Willamette Week|title=An (Alternate) Oral History of the Satyricon|date=October 16, 2013|author=Horton, Jay|accessdate=November 22, 2015}}</ref> through [[The Miracle Workers]]' frontman Gerry Mohr.{{sfn|Evans|1994|p=65}} The club is also notable for being the place where Love first crossed paths with her future husband, [[Nirvana (band)|Nirvana]] frontman [[Kurt Cobain]].  In a 2010 interview, she claimed she met Cobain there in 1988 at a [[Dharma Bums (band)|Dharma Bums]] concert where she was reading [[spoken word]] poetry,<ref>{{cite episode|network=Fuse|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=fgqt0ofwE3g|series=On The Record|title=Interview with Courtney Love|date=May 10, 2010|accessdate=May 14, 2018}}</ref> although other accounts state that the two met in January 1989 or 1990<ref name=beast>{{cite web|url=http://www.thedailybeast.com/articles/2014/03/04/the-moment-kurt-cobain-met-courtney-love.html|work=[[The Daily Beast]]|title=The Moment Kurt Cobain Met Courtney Love|date=April 5, 2014|author=Cross, Charles|accessdate=October 29, 2014|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170609113438/http://www.thedailybeast.com/the-moment-kurt-cobain-met-courtney-love|archivedate=June 9, 2017}}</ref> when Nirvana was playing at the club,{{sfn|Green|2003|pages=69\u201370}} and that they playfully wrestled in front of a [[jukebox]] that night.<ref name=beast/> [[Mark Arm]] of [[Mudhoney]] would later claim the story to be apocryphal, and that two in fact met while Mudhoney was touring with Love's band [[Hole (band)|Hole]] in Europe in 1991.{{sfn|Yarm|2011|p=256}} In a 2015 interview, Love clarified: \"It was at the Satyricon ... I sometimes lie and say which bands were playing but I actually don't remember. But Nirvana was obviously playing. He was cute, he was attractive, and he was funny ... Everyone always writes that the song that was playing [on the jukebox] was [[Living Colour]], but that wasn't it. It was \"Dear Friend\" by Flying Color.<ref>{{cite web|work=[[V (American magazine)|V]]|title=Courtney Love on ''Kurt Cobain: Montage of Heck''|url=https://www.vmagazine.com/site/content/4111/courtney-love-on-kurt-cobain-montage-of-heck|date=May 2015|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150905212809/https://www.vmagazine.com/site/content/4111/courtney-love-on-kurt-cobain-montage-of-heck|archivedate=September 5, 2015|author=Sandberg, Patrik}}</ref>\n\nCommenting on the various stories and lore surrounding the club, journalist Zach Dundas wrote: \"The written record of the club's existence{{en dash}}which can amount to no more than 1 percent of the Whole Truth{{en dash}}is a florid tale of excess, controversy, creative chaos. And, yes, artistic greatness.\"<ref name=notorious/>\n\n====1990s====\nIn 1990, a [[charity record|benefit]] [[LP record]] was put out for the club called \"''Satyricon ... the Album''\".  It included tracks from local punk acts such as Poison Idea, Dharma Bums and Napalm Beach.<ref name=zenorecords>{{cite web\n | url = http://zenorecords.com/product/satyricon-the-album-cdr/\n | title = Satyricon The Album (CDR)\n | work = zenorecords\n | accessdate = April 24, 2016\n}}</ref> Beginning in the early 1990s, Satyricon became a frequent host to [[grunge]] bands,<ref name=samson>{{cite book|title=Frommer's Seattle and Portland, '94-'95|publisher=Prentice Hall Travel|year=1994|p=[https://archive.org/details/frommerscomprehe00sams/page/242 242]|author=Samson, Karl|isbn=978-0-671-86659-4|url=https://archive.org/details/frommerscomprehe00sams/page/242}}</ref> including Nirvana,<ref>{{cite web|work=Spin|url=https://www.spin.com/2015/01/nirvana-unheard-concert-satyricon-dale-crover/|date=January 12, 2015|accessdate=May 16, 2018|title=Listen to a 25-Year-Old Nirvana Concert Bootleg Nobody's Ever Heard Before|author=Grebey, James}}</ref> [[Soundgarden]], [[Pearl Jam]], and Mudhoney, among others.<ref name=ithink/><ref name=hughley/> In  1993, Satyricon opened its own restaurant called ''Fellini'', a nod to the club's namesake.<ref name=wweek/>\n\n[[Dave Grohl]] played his first show with his post-Nirvana outfit [[Foo Fighters]] (after [[Death of Kurt Cobain|Cobain's suicide]]) at Satyricon.<ref>{{cite journal|work=Spin|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Z1BJTsbRdMEC&pg=PA44&dq=foo+fighters+satyricon&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjk5MftrovbAhWnxlQKHao7BToQ6AEIKTAA#v=onepage&q=foo%20fighters%20satyricon&f=false|title=Live!: Foo Fighters|p=44|date=June 1995|via=Google Books|volume=11|number=3|issn=0886-3032}} {{free access}}</ref> Other events, besides notable concerts, include a number of incidents involving notable people (including Courtney Love passing out) and a police riot in 1990.<ref name=notorious/>\n\n===Renovation and closure===\n[[File:F***ed Up (live at Satyricon, 2008).jpg|thumb|right|upright=1|[[Fucked Up]] performing at Satyricon, 2008]]\nIn May 2003, Satyricon abruptly closed and was slated to be taken over by the owners of another (former) club in town, Moody's.<ref name=hughley/> It reopened as an all-ages club in August 2006 under the management of the owners of the Loveland, an all-ages venue in Portland.<ref name=hughley>{{cite web\n | url = http://www.oregonlive.com/music/index.ssf/2010/10/post_19.html\n | title = Portland nightclub Satyricon says farewell with series of reunion shows\n | author = Marty Hughley\n | date = October 18, 2010\n | work = The Oregonian\n | accessdate = October 24, 2010\n}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wweek.com/portland/article-5915-local_news_reviews.html|work=Willamette Week|date=August 9, 2006|accessdate=September 11, 2012|title=Legendary Portland rock club Satyricon to reopen; Loveland to fade away}}</ref><ref>{{cite web\n | url = http://www.wweek.com/portland/blog-20441-satyricon_to_close_%28forever%29_in_october.html\n | title = Satyricon to Close (Forever) in October\n | author = Jarman, Casey\n | date =  August 3, 2010\n | work = Willamette Week\n | accessdate = February 4, 2012\n}}</ref> Mild renovations were undertaken, though a review of the club upon its reopening noted: \"The club looks the same ... eerily so. Same bar stools, same black paint. At the same time, it looks unfinished, like someone decided to remodel, ripped up a few boards and then totally slacked off.\"<ref>{{cite web|work=Portland Tribune|url=http://portlandtribune.com/component/content/article?id=102930|author=DiStefano, Anne Marie|date=September 21, 2006|accessdate=May 15, 2018|title=Satyricon lifts the curtain for next generation of fans}}</ref>\n\nIn October 2010, Ben Munat, the Satyricon's booking agent, organized thirteen \"''Farewell Satyricon Shows''\" for that month.<ref name=hughley/><ref>{{cite web|work=Portland Mercury|url=https://www.portlandmercury.com/endhits/archives/2010/08/06/the-end-of-satyricon-an-interview-with-the-fabled-clubs-co-ownerbooker-jeff-urquhart|title=The End of Satyricon: An Interview with the Fabled Club's Co-Owner/Booker, Jeff Urquhart|date=August 6, 2010|author=Caraeff, Ezra Ace|accessdate=May 9, 2018}}</ref> Bands included Big Daddy Meat Straw, the [[Dandy Warhols]] (with original drummer Eric Hedford, playing songs from first two albums with some original guitars), Pond, Poison Idea, and Napalm Beach,<ref name=Vondersmith/> with the final concert taking place on October 31, 2010.<ref name=long/> Commenting on the club's closure, owner Touhouliotis said: \"I had gotten tired. A place like that runs on creativity and energy; it's not automatic. And by the late '90s, the turn of the millennium, my energy wasn't there.\"<ref name=hughley/>\n\n===Demolition and aftermath===\nDemolition of the building began in July 2011,<ref>{{cite web|author=Hottle, Molly|date=July 27, 2011|url=http://www.oregonlive.com/portland/index.ssf/2011/07/demolition_begins_on_building.html|title=Demolition begins on building that once housed Satyricon nightclub|work=The Oregonian|accessdate=November 27, 2011}}</ref> after which many pieces of furniture, memorabilia, and parts of the building were \"unceremoniously given away to anyone interested.\"<ref name=long/> The urinal trough in the men's restroom was reportedly acquired by a [[tulip]] farm in [[Gresham, Oregon|Gresham]].<ref name=long/> The marquee above the club's entrance was believed to have been either stolen or destroyed in the demolition process, as it remained unaccounted for.<ref name=long>{{cite web|url=http://www.wweek.com/uncategorized/2017/05/19/the-long-lost-satyricon-sign-resurfaces-at-the-dandy-warhols-old-portland-wine-bar/|work=Willamette Week|title=The Long-Lost Satyricon Sign Resurfaces at the Dandy Warhols' Old Portland Wine Bar|author=Horton, Jay|date=May 19, 2017|accessdate=May 16, 2018}}</ref> In 2017, [[Courtney Taylor-Taylor]], frontman of the Dandy Warhols, reported that he had found the marquee, which he had installed at The Old Portland, a wine bar he opened in 2016.<ref name=long/> The location of the original building is now home to the nonprofit MacDonald Center service center and studio apartments to serve low-income residents.<ref name=Vondersmith>{{cite web | url = http://portlandtribune.com/component/content/article?id=37020\n | title = Satyricon refuses to go quietly\n | author = Vondersmith, Jason\n | date =  September 29, 2010\n | work = Portland Tribune\n | accessdate = April 24, 2016\n}}</ref>\n\n==In popular culture==\nThe club was used as a filming location for [[Gus Van Sant]]'s 1985 film, ''[[Mala Noche]]''.<ref name=\"alternate\"/> In 2013, after its demolition, a documentary about the club, ''Satyricon: Madness and Glory'', was released.<ref name=doc>{{cite web|work=[[KPTV]]|url=http://www.kptv.com/story/23706685/satyricon-movie-remembers-infamous-portland-nightclub|title=Satyricon movie remembers infamous Portland nightclub|date=October 16, 2013|author=FOX 12 Staff|accessdate=May 16, 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Notable bands==\nThe following are documented bands that notably performed at Satyricon:{{citation needed|date=May 2018}}<ref name=\"hughley\"/><ref name=\"alternate\"/><ref name=\"Martin James\"/><ref name=\"Pearl Jam venues\"/><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.setlist.fm/venue/satyricon-portland-or-usa-2bd6d472.html?page=27 |title=Satyricon Portland Concert Setlists |work=setlist.fm |accessdate=April 24, 2016}}</ref>\n \n{{columns-list|colwidth=30em|\n*[[90 Proof]]\n*[[The Acc\u00fcsed]]\n*[[All Out (band)|All Out]]\n*[[Amy Denio]]\n*[[Armored Saint]]\n*[[Bodybag]]\n*[[Camper Van Beethoven]]\n*[[Cannibal Corpse]]\n*[[Chevelle (band)|Chevelle]]\n*[[Chrome Dog with Bif Naked]]\n*[[Clever Cadavers]]\n*The Confidentials\n*[[The Dandy Warhols]]\n*[[The Dead Milkmen]]\n*[[Dead Moon]]\n*[[Deli Creeps]]\n*[[The Delinquents (band)|The Delinquents]]\n*[[Dharma Bums]]\n*[[Elliott Smith]]<ref>https://www.setlist.fm/setlist/elliott-smith/1999/satyricon-portland-or-7bdf8e0c.html</ref>\n*[[Everclear (band)|Everclear]]\n* [[Final Warning]]\n*[[The Flaming Lips]]\n*[[Foo Fighters]]\n*[[GWAR]]\n*[[Green Day]]\n*[[Green River (band)|Green River]]\n*[[Greg Sage (band)|Greg Sage]]\n*[[Heatmiser]]\n*Hitting Birth\n*The Jackals\n*The Jimmies\n*[[Juliana Hatfield]]\n*[[The Hetros]]\n*[[King Black Acid (band)|King Black Acid]]\n*[[L7 (band)|L7]]\n*[[Local H]]\n*[[Lockjaw (band)|Lockjaw]]\n*[[Meat Puppets]]\n*[[Melvins]]\n*[[The Mentors]]\n*[[Mojo Nixon]]\n*[[Mother Love Bone]]\n*[[Mudhoney]]\n*[[Naked Violence]]\n*[[Napalm Beach]]\n*[[Nightcaps (band)|Nightcaps]]\n*[[Nirvana (band)|Nirvana]]\n*[[Oasis (band)|Oasis]]\n*[[Obituaries (band)|The Obituaries]]\n*[[Pavement (band)|Pavement]]\n*[[Pearl Jam]]\n*[[Poison Idea]]\n*[[Pond (American band)|Pond]]\n*[[Portugal. The Man]]\n*[[The Presidents of the United States of America (band)|The Presidents of the United States of America]]\n*[[Queens of the Stone Age]]\n*[[Richmond Fontaine]]\n*[[The Reeds Mill Investigation]]\n*[[Saint Vitus (band)|Saint Vitus]]\n*[[Sic Fucks]]\n*[[Sleater-Kinney]]\n*[[Sloppy Seconds]]\n*[[Snowbird (band)|Snowbird]]\n*[[Soul Asylum]]\n*[[Spastic Blur]]\n*[[Speed Weenie]]\n*[[Spoon (band)|Spoon]]\n*[[Sweaty Nipples]]\n*[[Tattooed Corpse]]\n*[[Voivod (band)|Voivod]]\n*[[Ween (band)|Ween]]\n*[[Wehrmacht]]\n*[[White Zombie (band)|White Zombie]]\n*[[Wipers]]\n*[[Wreck-Creation]]\n*[[Wretched Death]]\n*[[Zipgun]]}}\n\n== See also ==\n* [[X-Ray Cafe]]\n* [[La Luna (Portland, Oregon)|La Luna]]\n*[[Music of Oregon]]\n\n==Notes==\n{{noteslist}}\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==Works cited==\n*{{cite book|last=Evans|first=Liz|title=Women, Sex and Rock'n'roll: In Their Own Words|year=1994|publisher=Pandora|isbn=978-0-044-40900-7|oclc=494693178|ref=harv|url=https://archive.org/details/womensexrocknrol0000unse}}\n*{{cite book|last=Green|first=Joey|title=How They Met: Fateful Encounters of Famous Lovebirds, Rivals, Partners in Crime|publisher=Black Dog Publishing|year=2003|isbn=978-1-4223-6673-8|ref=harv|oclc=52621239}}\n*{{cite web|url=http://www.oregon.gov/olcc/docs/final_orders/final_orders_1986/satyricon_85_l_032.pdf|author=Oregon Liquor Control Commission (OLCC)|work=Oregon Liquor Control Commission|title=Final Order: Satyricon|ref={{sfnref|Oregon Liquor Control Commission|1986}}|format=PDF|publisher=State of Oregon|year=1986}}\n*{{cite book|last=Schultz|first=William Todd|year=2015|title=Torment Saint: The Life of Elliott Smith|publisher=Bloomsbury USA|ref=harv|isbn= 978-1-620-40784-4}}\n*{{cite book|last1=Trombold|first1=John|last2=Donahue|first2=Peter, eds.|year=2017|title=Reading Portland: The City in Prose|publisher=University of Washington Press|ref=harv|isbn=978-0-295-99760-5}}\n*{{cite book|last=Yarm|first=Mark|title=Everybody Loves Our Town: An Oral History of Grunge|isbn=978-0-307-46444-6|location=New York|publisher=Three Rivers Press|year=2011|ref=harv|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=z-44p7V2TrUC&printsec=frontcover|oclc=935232799}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category|Satyricon (nightclub)}}\n*[https://www.setlist.fm/venue/satyricon-portland-or-usa-2bd6d472.html List of concerts] at Satyricon via Setlist.fm\n\n{{Old Town Chinatown, Portland, Oregon}}\n{{coord| 45.524209 | -122.676773 | type:landmark_region:US-OR_source:googlemaps_dim:30 | display=title}}<!-- geocoded \"125 Northwest 6th Avenue, Portland, Oregon\" -->\n\n[[Category:Defunct nightclubs in Portland, Oregon]]\n[[Category:Former music venues in the United States]]\n[[Category:Demolished music venues in the United States]]\n[[Category:Demolished buildings and structures in Portland, Oregon]]\n[[Category:Old Town Chinatown, Portland, Oregon]]\n[[Category:1984 establishments in Oregon]]\n[[Category:2010 disestablishments in Oregon]]\n[[Category:Northwest Portland, Oregon]]\n", "name_user": "Gilderob", "label": "safe", "comment": "Added Bevis Frond to list of bands.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Satyricon_(nightclub)"}
