{"title_page": "Skopje 2014", "text_new": "{{Update|date=December 2016}}\n[[File:Skopje 2014 - Museum of the Macedonian Struggle and National Theatre.JPG|thumb|500px|View of the buildings finished after the 1963 earthquake (2014).]]\n'''Skopje 2014''' ({{lang-mk|\u0421\u043a\u043e\u043f\u0458\u0435 2014}}) was a project financed by the [[Government of the Republic of North Macedonia|Macedonian government]] of the then-ruling nationalist party [[VMRO-DPMNE]], with the official purpose of giving the capital [[Skopje]] a more classical appeal.<ref>EastWest Institute (2000). Jonathan P. Stein, ed. The Politics of National Minority Participation in Post-Communist Europe: State-Building, Democracy, and Ethnic Mobilization. M.E. Sharpe. p. 91. {{ISBN|978-0-7656-0528-3}}.</ref> The project, officially announced in 2010, consisted mainly of the construction of colleges, museums and government buildings, as well as the erection of monuments depicting historical figures from the [[Macedonia (region)|region of Macedonia]]. Around 20 buildings and over 40 monuments were to be constructed as part of the project.<ref name=\"Marusic2\" />\n\nThe project was seen as politically controversial in its nature and as a [[nation-building]] endeavour, as it tried to further impose the [[Macedonian historiography|narrative of Macedonian history]], promoting a Macedonian identity with  unbroken continuity from antiquity over the Middle Ages to the modern times.<ref>Janev, G. (2015). \u2018Skopje 2014\u2019: erasing memories, building history. In M. Couroucli, & T. Marinov (Eds.), Balkan heritages: Negotiating history and culture (pp. 111-130). Taylor & Francis, 2017, {{ISBN|1134800754}}.</ref> Skopje 2014 has also generated controversy for its cost, for which estimates range from 80 to 500 million euros.<ref name=\"Bugjevac\">{{cite news |url=http://www.globusmagazin.com.mk/?ItemID=C18D740B2343534A8B173AAD06639F3A|title=\u0421\u041a\u041e\u041f\u0408\u0415 \u040c\u0415 \u0423\u041c\u0420\u0415 \u041e\u0414 \u041d\u0415\u0412\u041a\u0423\u0421|last=Bugjevac|first=Dejan |year=2007 |work=Globus |language=Macedonian|accessdate=8 June 2012}}</ref><ref name=\"Koteska\">{{cite news|url=http://www.artmargins.com/index.php/2-articles/655-troubles-with-history-skopje-2014|title=Troubles with History: Skopje 2014|last=Koteska|first=Jasna|date=29 December 2011|work=Art Margins Online |accessdate=8 June 2012|location=Republic of Macedonia}}</ref>\n\nThe Skopje 2014 project encompassed the construction, from 2010 to 2014, of 136 structures built at a cost of more than US$700 million.<ref>The New York Times International Edition, October 14, 2016, pg. 19</ref>\n\n[[File:Skopje X44.JPG|thumb|[[Macedonia Square, Skopje|Macedonia Square]] after the addition of many monuments and fa\u00e7ade reconstructions]]\n\n==Background==\n[[File:Skopje-razglednica 014.jpg|thumb|250px|The National Theatre and Kale Fortress before the 1963 earthquake]]\n[[File:Plaza de Macedonia, Skopie, Macedonia, 2014-04-17, DD 70.JPG|thumb|250px|View toward [[Macedonia Square, Skopje|Macedonia Square]] from the [[Stone Bridge (Skopje)|Stone Bridge]] in July 2011. Visible are the statues of Dame Gruev, Goce Del\u010dev, Tsar Samuil, and the under construction Warrior on a Horse monument]]\n\nThe [[1963 Skopje earthquake]] destroyed approximately 80% of the city, including most of the neoclassical buildings in the central part of Skopje.<ref name=\"MRT\">[http://www.mrt.com.mk/en//index.php?option=com_content&task=view&id=3316&Itemid=27 Marking the 44th anniversary of the catastrophic 1963 Skopje earthquake] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070930210952/http://www.mrt.com.mk/en//index.php?option=com_content&task=view&id=3316&Itemid=27 |date=2007-09-30 }} [[Macedonian Radio-Television|MRT]], Thursday, 26 July 2007</ref> The rebuilding that followed saw the construction of mostly plain [[modernist architecture]]. This is one of the reasons given by the VMRO-DPMNE government for the necessity of the project, to give Skopje a more monumental and visually pleasing image. Another reason is to restore the missing sense of national pride and create a more metropolitan atmosphere.<ref name=\"Marusic\">{{cite news|url=http://www.balkaninsight.com/en/gallery/skopje-2014|title=Skopje 2014: The new face of Macedonia, updated|last=Marusic|first=Sini\u0161a|date=11 May 2012|publisher=BalkanInsight|accessdate=27 July 2012|location=Skopje}}</ref> In a speech at the opening of [[Porta Macedonia]] in January 2012, then Prime Minister [[Nikola Gruevski]] stated that Skopje 2014 was his idea.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://macedoniaonline.eu/content/view/20045/45/|title=PM Gruevski: Yes, Skopje 2014 was my Idea|date=7 January 2012|publisher=MINA|accessdate=30 July 2012}}</ref>\n\n===Criticism===\n{{see also|Antiquization|Macedonian historiography}}\nThe Skopje 2014 project has been criticized by various groups since the time it was first announced. The cost of the project is estimated at anywhere from 80 to more than 500 million euros<ref>[http://edition.cnn.com/2011/10/04/world/europe/macedonia-skopje-2014/index.html Is Macedonia's capital being turned into a theme park?], CNN, October 10, 2011</ref><ref>[http://www.balkaninsight.com/en/article/macedonian-culture-strategy-milestone-or-wish-list  Macedonian Culture Strategy: Milestone or Wish List?], BalkanInsight, 15 Nov 12</ref> and is seen by many as a waste of resources in a country with high unemployment and poverty. The project is also believed by critics to be a distraction from these problems.<ref name=\"Marusic\" />\n\nThe [[Social Democratic Union of Macedonia]], the main opposition party, opposes the project and has alleged that the monuments could have cost six to ten times less than what the government paid.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.skopjediem.com/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=9407:sdsm-allegations-at-government-on-skopje-2014-project-&catid=1:latest-news&Itemid=81|archive-url=https://archive.is/20130104174531/http://www.skopjediem.com/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=9407:sdsm-allegations-at-government-on-skopje-2014-project-&catid=1:latest-news&Itemid=81|url-status=dead|archive-date=4 January 2013|title=SDSM Allegations at Government on Skopje 2014 Project|date=30 March 2011|publisher=SkopjeDiem|accessdate=30 July 2012|location=Skopje}}</ref>\n\nThe project is seen as a part of the government's \"antiquisation\" policy, in which the country seeks to claim [[Ancient Macedonians|ancient Macedonian]] figures like [[Alexander the Great]] and [[Philip II of Macedon]] for itself. The timing of the project, following the country's non-invitation to NATO due to its continued [[Macedonia naming dispute|naming dispute]] with [[Greece]], has led to speculation that it is retaliation or an attempt to put pressure on Greece.<ref name=\"Georgievski\">''Ghosts of the past endanger Macedonia's future''. Boris Georgievski, BalkanInsight, October 27, 2009 [http://www.balkaninsight.com/en/article/ghosts-of-the-past-endanger-macedonia-s-future].</ref> Some residents see the scheme as the embodiment of nationalism by a conservative government focused as much on giving the metropolis a facelift as changing the nation's history and have described it as a mini-[[Las Vegas]]<ref>The Guardian, [https://www.theguardian.com/world/2011/aug/14/alexander-great-macedonia-warrior-horse Macedonia statue: Alexander the Great or a warrior on a horse?], Sunday 14 August 2011</ref> while others appreciate its classical nod to the past.<ref>[http://www.euronews.com/2011/05/05/the-changing-face-of-skopje/ The Changing Face of Skopje], Euronews.com, May 5, 2011</ref>\n\n[[Sam Vaknin]], a former adviser to Nikola Gruevski, has stated that the project is not anti-Greek or anti-Bulgarian, but anti-Albanian. In an interview, he said \"Antiquisation has a double goal, which is to marginalise the Albanians and create an identity that will not allow Albanians to become Macedonians.\"<ref name=\"Georgievski\" /><ref name=\"StefoskaStojanov364\"/> To shift attention from Albanians being absent from the Skopje 2014 project, the Macedonian government agreed to fund [[Skanderbeg Square, Skopje|Skanderbeg Square]] built around the existing Skanderbeg monument in the part of Skopje with a majority Albanian population.<ref name=\"StefoskaStojanov364\">{{cite journal|last1=Stefoska|first1=Irena|last2=Stojanov|first2=Darko|title=A tale in stone and bronze: old/new strategies for political mobilization in the Republic of Macedonia|url=https://www.cambridge.org/core/services/aop-cambridge-core/content/view/29F560037E1931D083C10F7B56D96893/S0090599200032141a.pdf/tale_in_stone_and_bronze_oldnew_strategies_for_political_mobilization_in_the_republic_of_macedonia.pdf|journal=Nationalities Papers|volume=45|issue=3|year=2017|pages=364|doi=10.1080/00905992.2017.1308346|ref=harv}}</ref> Later additions to the Skopje 2014  project were made that included depictions of ethnic Albanians in the monuments such as [[Nexhat Agolli]], [[Josif Bageri]], and [[Pjet\u00ebr Bogdani]], as well as others on the [[Art Bridge]].\n\nArchitects have criticized the aesthetics of the project and believe the money could have been spent on constructing modern buildings.<ref name=\"Marusic\" /> It has also been described as nationalist [[kitsch]]<ref>Maria Couroucli and Tchavdar Marinov eds., Balkan Heritages: Negotiating History and Culture, British School at Athens - Modern Greek and Byzantine Studies, Taylor & Francis, 2017, {{ISBN|1134800754}}, p. 218.</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://balkans.courriers.info/spip.php?page=dossier&id_article=18171|title=Mac\u00e9doine : Skopje 2014, kitsch nationaliste et foire aux antiquit\u00e9s|year=2012|publisher=Le Courrier des Balkans|language=French|accessdate=30 July 2012}}</ref> which \"brings unknown history\" to the citizens<ref>Borian Jovanovski Al Jazeera, 18 March 2015, [http://www.aljazeera.com/programmes/peopleandpower/2015/03/macedonia-facade-150318135440964.html]: \"Talking about this project Skopje 2014, yes it's damaging to inter-ethnic relations, it's not reflecting the multi-cultural society that Macedonia is. But on the other hand you have an Albanian party in the government - and they agree - so in a way they have responsibility for what's going on too. It's obvious that it is damaging inter-ethnic relations which are anyway fragile and damaging Macedonian national identity too because it brings us to history that is unknown to us, in which we are a kind of successor to Alexander the Great. This is not true because Alexander the Great is famous because he enlarged the Hellenic culture. We are Slavs who are not Hellenic at all.\"</ref> and current prime minister [[Zoran Zaev]] has labeled it an \"idiotic project\".<ref>Zoran Zaev, S\u00fcddeutsche Zeitung, 27 December 2016, [http://www.sueddeutsche.de/politik/mazedonien-hinter-neuen-fassaden-1.3311464]: \"Mit dem idiotischen Skopje-2014-Projekt und der zusammenh\u00e4ngenden Pseudo-Geschichtsschreibung, die Alexander den Gro\u00dfen f\u00fcr Mazedonien reklamiert, haben wir nicht nur Griechenland provoziert, sondern auch viel internationale Unterst\u00fctzung f\u00fcr unsere Position verloren.\" (English translation: With the idiotic Skopje 2014 project and the related pseudo-historiography that claims Alexander the Great for Macedonia, we have not only provoked Greece, but also lost much international support for our position.)</ref>\n\n===2018===\nIn late February 2018, the government and institutions of the Republic of Macedonia announced the halt of the Skopje 2014 program and begun removing its [[Macedonian nationalism|controversial]] monuments and statues. The [[Ministry of Culture (Macedonia)|Macedonian Ministry of Culture]] also has set up a Commission to envisage the possibility of removing the rest of them, such as of [[Alexander the Great]] and [[Philip II of Macedon]]. As a first step, the monument of [[Andon Kyoseto]] was dismantled, as one of the mostly disputed of the project.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.mia.mk/EN/Inside/RenderSingleNews/289/134124689/|title=City of Skopje starting to take action on Skopje 2014 project: Mayor|publisher=Macedonian Information Agency|accessdate=9 March 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.balkaneu.com/a-skopje-2014-monument-is-removed/|title=A \"Skopje 2014\" monument is removed|publisher=IBNA|accessdate=9 March 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.euscoop.com/en/2018/2/22/statue-removed-macedonia|title=Macedonia Removes the Skopje 2014 Statue of Andon Kyoseto|publisher=EUscoop|accessdate=9 March 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.amna.gr/en/article/232954/Skopje-starts-removal-of-irredentist-statues-put-up-by-Gruevski-government|title=Skopje starts removal of 'irredentist' statues put up by Gruevski government|publisher=AMNA|accessdate=9 March 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.balkaneu.com/removal-of-monuments-in-skopje-whose-turn-is-next/|title=Removal of monuments in Skopje, whose turn is next?|publisher=IBNA|accessdate=9 March 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://en.protothema.gr/skopje-authorities-start-to-tear-down-nationalistic-statues/|title=Skopje authorities start to tear down nationalistic statues|publisher=Proto Thema|accessdate=9 March 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.balkaninsight.com/en/article/macedonia-removes-divisive-court-statue-02-22-2018|title=Divisive Revolutionary's Statue Vanishes from Macedonian Capital|publisher=BIRN|accessdate=9 March 2018}}</ref> In June 2018 the Macedonian Government announced that the monuments would be renamed and marked with inscriptions honouring Greek-Macedonian friendship.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.balkaninsight.com/en/article/divisive-skopje-2014-landmarks-find-new-purpose-06-14-2018|title=Macedonia to Rename Divisive Statues that Irked Greece|publisher=BIRN|accessdate=25 September 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Plans==\n\n===Bridges===\n\n====New bridge constructions====\n\n=====Art Bridge=====\n\n{{main|Art Bridge}}\n\nThe Skopje 2014 project calls for two new pedestrian bridges to be built across the [[Vardar River|Vardar]] in the centre of the city. One is the Art Bridge, which is being constructed between the Freedom Bridge and the also under-construction Eye Bridge. It is expected to cost 2.5 million euros. The bridge will include 29 sculptures, with 14 at each end and one in the centre. It will be 83 metres (272.3 feet) in length and 9.2&nbsp;m (30.2&nbsp;ft) in width, while the central part of the bridge will be 12&nbsp;m (39.4&nbsp;ft) wide.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://utrinski.com.mk/default.asp?ItemID=C71B15A20E1CA24AABF563D72712711D|title=\u041c\u043e\u0441\u0442\u043e\u0442 \u043d\u0430 \u0443\u043c\u0435\u0442\u043d\u043e\u0441\u0442\u0430 \u0441\u0435 \u0438\u0441\u043a\u0430\u0447\u0438 \u043d\u0430 \u043a\u043e\u043d\u0441\u0442\u0440\u0443\u043a\u0446\u0438\u0458\u0430\u0442\u0430|date=April 8, 2012|publisher=Utrinski Vesnik|language=Macedonian|accessdate=19 June 2012|location=Skopje|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120613224413/http://www.utrinski.com.mk/default.asp?ItemID=C71B15A20E1CA24AABF563D72712711D|archivedate=13 June 2012|df=}}</ref>\n\n=====Eye Bridge=====\nThe other bridge being constructed as part of the project is the Eye Bridge. Situated between the [[Stone Bridge (Skopje)|Stone Bridge]] and the under-construction Art Bridge, it began construction in 2011. The pedestrian bridge will include 28 sculptures and will cost around 1.5 million euros.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://daily.mk/skopje-mostot-oko-konechno-pochna-da-se-gradi?forward=802275|title=\u041c\u043e\u0441\u0442\u043e\u0442 \u041e\u043a\u043e \u043a\u043e\u043d\u0435\u0447\u043d\u043e \u043f\u043e\u0447\u043d\u0430 \u0434\u0430 \u0441\u0435 \u0433\u0440\u0430\u0434\u0438|date=July 29, 2011|publisher=Daily.mk|language=Macedonian|accessdate=19 June 2012|location=Skopje}}</ref>\n\n====Existing bridge renovations====\n\n=====Freedom Bridge=====\n[[File:Puente Goce Delcev, Skopie, Macedonia, 2014-04-16, DD 52.JPG|thumb|250px|Aerial view of the renovated Goce Del\u010dev Bridge]]\n\nThe project also includes plans to renovate existing bridges in central Skopje, one of which is the Freedom Bridge, which connects Vojvoda Vasil Ad\u017eilarski Street in [[Centar Municipality (Skopje)|Centar Municipality]] to Stiv Naumov Street in [[\u010cair Municipality]]. First constructed in 1936, the renovation began in 2011 and is expected to be completed in May, 2014. The total cost will be roughly 1.15 million euros.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.kirilica.com.mk/vest.asp?id=69962|title=1.140.000 \u0435\u0432\u0440\u0430 \u0437\u0430 \u043e\u0433\u0440\u0430\u0434\u0430\u0442\u0430 \u043d\u0430 \u043c\u043e\u0441\u0442\u043e\u0442 \u043a\u0430\u0458 \u0425\u043e\u043b\u0438\u0434\u0435\u0458 \u0418\u043d|date=May 9, 2012|publisher=\u041a\u0438\u0440\u0438\u043b\u0438\u0446\u0430|language=Macedonian|accessdate=2012-06-12}}</ref>\n\n=====Goce Del\u010dev Bridge=====\nThe renovation of the Goce Del\u010dev Bridge, which connects Ilinden Boulevard in Centar to Goce Del\u010dev Boulevard in \u010cair across the Vardar, began on April 11, 2011<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.build.mk/?p=7238|title=\"\u0411\u0430\u0440\u043e\u043a\u043d\u0430\" \u043e\u0433\u0440\u0430\u0434\u0430 \u0437\u0430 \u043c\u043e\u0441\u0442\u043e\u0442 \u0413\u043e\u0446\u0435 \u0414\u0435\u043b\u0447\u0435\u0432|date=4 November 2011|publisher=build.mk|language=Macedonian|accessdate=12 June 2012}}</ref> and finished later in the year. The renovation included new gold-coloured fencing and 26 lampposts. The project cost roughly 500,000 euros, including 60,000 euros for the new lighting.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.build.mk/?p=10183|title=\u041c\u043e\u0441\u0442\u043e\u0442 \u0413\u043e\u0446\u0435 \u0414\u0435\u043b\u0447\u0435\u0432 \u0432\u043e \u043d\u043e\u0432\u043e \u0441\u0432\u0435\u0442\u043b\u043e|date=23 October 2011|publisher=build.mk|language=Macedonian|accessdate=12 June 2012}}</ref> Four statues depicting lions, two at each end, were also placed on the bridge in 2010. The ones on the western side were cast in [[Florence]] and cost 1.5 million euros.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.build.mk/?p=4837|title=\u041f\u043e\u0441\u0442\u0430\u0432\u0435\u043d\u0438 \u0434\u0432\u0430 \u043b\u0430\u0432\u0430 \u043d\u0430 \u043c\u043e\u0441\u0442\u043e\u0442 \u0413\u043e\u0446\u0435 \u0414\u0435\u043b\u0447\u0435\u0432|date=24 August 2010|publisher=build.mk|language=Macedonian|accessdate=12 June 2012}}</ref>\n\n=====Revolution Bridge=====\nThe Revolution Bridge, first built in 1963 across the Vardar connecting Ko\u010do Racin Boulevard in Centar to Krste Misirkov Boulevard in \u010cair, was also renovated as part of the Skopje 2014 project. It began on December 9, 2010 and was completed in May, 2011. The renovation included basic repairs as well as the installation of 22 lampposts and iron-wrought fencing. The renovation cost 450,000 euros.<ref name=\"\u0441\u0438\u0442\u0435\u043b\">{{cite web|url=http://www.sitel.com.mk/dnevnik/makedonija/pushten-vo-upotreba-rekonstruiraniot-%E2%80%9Emost-na-revolucijata%E2%80%9C|title=\u041f\u0443\u0448\u0442\u0435\u043d \u0432\u043e \u0443\u043f\u043e\u0442\u0440\u0435\u0431\u0430 \u0440\u0435\u043a\u043e\u043d\u0441\u0442\u0440\u0443\u0438\u0440\u0430\u043d\u0438\u043e\u0442 \"\u041c\u043e\u0441\u0442 \u043d\u0430 \u0420\u0435\u0432\u043e\u043b\u0443\u0446\u0438\u0458\u0430\u0442\u0430\"|last=\u0411\u043e\u0448\u043a\u043e\u0432\u0441\u043a\u0430|first=\u0415\u043b\u0435\u043d\u0430|date=May 16, 2011|publisher=\u0421\u0438\u0442\u0435\u043b|language=Macedonian|accessdate=2012-06-12}}</ref>\n\n===Cultural buildings===\n\n====Macedonian Philharmonic Orchestra hall====\nNotable in Skopje 2014 for its bold modern architecture as opposed to the usual neoclassical style seen in the project, the under-construction concert hall to house the Macedonian Philharmonic Orchestra is one of the first buildings to begin construction in the project, with the cornerstone having been laid in June 2009. The exterior of the building is nearing completion. The concert hall is planned to have excellent acoustics and will have a capacity of 900 seats.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://kurir.mk/makedonija/kultura/49599-FOTO-Kako-ke-izgleda-novata-sala-na-Makedonskata-Filharmonija|title=\u0424\u041e\u0422\u041e: \u041a\u0430\u043a\u043e \u045c\u0435 \u0438\u0437\u0433\u043b\u0435\u0434\u0430 \u043d\u043e\u0432\u0430\u0442\u0430 \u0441\u0430\u043b\u0430 \u043d\u0430 \u041c\u0430\u043a\u0435\u0434\u043e\u043d\u0441\u043a\u0430\u0442\u0430 \u0424\u0438\u043b\u0445\u0430\u0440\u043c\u043e\u043d\u0438\u0458\u0430?|date=14 November 2011|publisher=Kurir|language=Macedonian|accessdate=5 July 2012|location=Skopje|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120220164605/http://www.kurir.mk/makedonija/kultura/49599-FOTO-Kako-ke-izgleda-novata-sala-na-Makedonskata-Filharmonija|archivedate=20 February 2012|df=}}</ref>\n\n====Museum of Archaeology====\n[[File:MuseumofArchaeologySkopje.jpg|thumb|220px|The completed Museum of Archaeology]]\n\nThe Museum of Archaeology began construction in 2009 and is expected to be formally opened in September, 2014.<ref name=\"Vasilevski\">{{cite news |url=http://www.novamakedonija.com.mk/NewsDetal.asp?vest=491482343&id=14&setIzdanie=23147|title=\u0412\u043e \u043c\u0443\u0437\u0435\u0458\u043e\u0442, \u043e\u0441\u0432\u0435\u043d \u0430\u0440\u0445\u0435\u043e\u043b\u043e\u0433\u0438\u0458\u0430, \u045c\u0435 \u0438\u043c\u0430 \u0438 \u043f\u0440\u0438\u043a\u0430\u0437\u043d\u0430 \u0437\u0430 \u0435\u0434\u043d\u0430 \u0432\u0435\u043b\u0438\u0447\u0435\u0441\u0442\u0432\u0435\u043d\u0430 \u0438\u0441\u0442\u043e\u0440\u0438\u0458\u0430|last=Vasilevski|first=\u017darko|publisher=Nova Makedonija|language=Macedonian|accessdate=3 May 2014}}</ref> Although the building will primarily serve as a museum, it will also house the Constitutional Court and the National Archive of the Republic of Macedonia. It is situated on the eastern bank of the [[Vardar]], across the river from [[Macedonia Square, Skopje|Macedonia Square]]. The exterior of the museum is almost complete, as of June 2012, and is among the more monumental buildings of the project, with its [[Greek Revival]] architecture.<ref name=\"Ivanovska\">{{cite news|url=http://www.dnevnik.com.mk/?ItemID=DC1E632C696096498994678CDACAFDF6|title=\u0410\u0440\u0445\u0435\u043e\u043b\u043e\u0448\u043a\u0438 \u043c\u0443\u0437\u0435\u0458 \u0432\u043e \u0446\u0435\u043d\u0442\u0430\u0440\u043e\u0442 \u043d\u0430 \u0421\u043a\u043e\u043f\u0458\u0435 |last=Ivanovska|first=Vesna|date=January 21, 2009|work=Dnevnik|language=Macedonian|accessdate=22 June 2012|location=Skopje}}</ref> [[VMRO-DPMNE]], the ruling party, states the budget for the construction as 436,000,000 [[Macedonian denar|denars]].<ref name=\"VMRO-DPMNE\">{{cite web|url=http://vmro-dpmne.org.mk/wp-content/uploads/documents/VMRO%20programa%202014-2018%20v2a.pdf|title=\u041f\u0440\u043e\u0431\u0435\u0440\u0435\u043d\u043e: \u041f\u0440\u043e\u0435\u043a\u0442\u0438 \u043a\u043e\u0438 \u0448\u0442\u043e \u0434\u043e\u043a\u0430\u0436\u0430\u043d\u043e \u0441\u0435 \u043e\u0441\u0442\u0430\u0440\u0442\u0443\u0432\u0430\u0430\u0442 |publisher=VMRO-DPMNE |accessdate=3 May 2014}}</ref>\n\n====Museum of the Macedonian Struggle====\n{{Multiple image\n | align     = left\n | direction = vertical\n | width     = 220\n | image1    = Muzej na VMRO 016.jpg\n | image2    = Museo de Lucha Macedonia, Skopie, Macedonia, 2014-04-16, DD 99.JPG\n | footer    = The completed [[Museum of the Macedonian Struggle (Skopje)|Museum of the Macedonian Struggle]]\n}}\n\n{{main|Museum of the Macedonian Struggle (Skopje)}}\n\nThe Museum of the Macedonian Struggle for Statehood and Independence \u2212 Museum of VMRO and Museum of the Victims of the Communist Regime exhibits the strive for an independent Macedonian nation from the [[Ottoman Empire]] and later [[Socialist Federal Republic of Yugoslavia|Yugoslavia]]. It is divided into 16 departments and includes over 100 wax figures of historical individuals. The museum lies on the eastern bank of the Vardar River just northwest of the Museum of Archaeology, opposite Macedonia Square. Construction began in June 2008 and it formally opened on September 10, 2011. The total cost of the museum, which covers 2,500 m<sup>2</sup> (26,909.8&nbsp;ft<sup>2</sup>), was roughly 10 million euros.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.build.mk/?p=9561|title=\u0424\u041e\u0422\u041e \u0412\u0415\u0421\u0422: \u0421\u0432\u0435\u0447\u0435\u043d\u043e \u043e\u0442\u0432\u043e\u0440\u0435\u043d \u041c\u0443\u0437\u0435\u0458\u0441\u043a\u0438\u043e\u0442 \u043a\u043e\u043c\u043f\u043b\u0435\u043a\u0441 \"\u041c\u0430\u043a\u0435\u0434\u043e\u043d\u0441\u043a\u0430 \u0431\u043e\u0440\u0431\u0430\"|date=September 9, 2011|publisher=build.mk|language=Macedonian|accessdate=19 June 2012|location=Skopje}}</ref>\n\n{{Multiple image\n | align     = right\n | direction = vertical\n | width     = 220\n | image1    = Makedonski Naroden Teatar 2013 15.JPG\n | image2    = Teatro Nacional, Skopie, Macedonia, 2014-04-17, DD 93.JPG\n | footer    = The completed National Theatre\n}}\n\n====National Theatre====\nThe former National Theatre destroyed in the [[1963 Skopje earthquake]] will be completely reconstructed, as part of the Skopje 2014 project. Construction of the building, however, began in December 2007, three years before the official announcing of Skopje 2014. Construction was originally planned to be completed in 2009, though it ended up being completed a few years after.<ref name=\"Factor\">{{cite news|url=http://faktor.mk/archives/102033|title=\u0421\u0442\u0430\u0440\u0438\u043e\u0442 \u0442\u0435\u0430\u0442\u0430\u0440 \u0443\u0448\u0442\u0435 \"\u0433\u043e\u043b\u0442\u0430\" \u043f\u0430\u0440\u0438|date=10 April 2014|publisher=Factor|language=Macedonian|accessdate=3 May 2014}}</ref> The theatre stands on its original location on the eastern bank of the Vardar. The cost is estimated to be at least 6 million euros<ref name=\"Mitevska\">{{cite news|url=http://www.utrinski.com.mk/?ItemID=EB377439F9568B45B8D60B595B5C157E|title=\u0417\u0430\u043f\u043e\u0447\u043d\u0430 \u0438\u0437\u0433\u0440\u0430\u0434\u0431\u0430\u0442\u0430 \u043d\u0430 \u043d\u043e\u0432\u0438\u043e\u0442 \u041c\u041d\u0422|last=Mitevska|first=Liljana|date=7 December 2007|publisher=Utrinski Vesnik|language=Macedonian|accessdate=5 July 2012|location=Skopje}}</ref> and may be as high as 30 million euros.<ref name=\"Marusic2\">{{cite news|url=http://balkanstory.wordpress.com/2012/06/07/skopje-2014-forges-ahead-despite-macedonian-crisis/|title=Skopje 2014 Forges Ahead Despite Macedonian Crisis|last=Marusic|first=Sinisa|publisher=Balkan Story|accessdate=30 July 2012|location=Skopje}}</ref>\n\n===Fa\u00e7ade reconstructions===\n[[File:SkopjeNewFa\u00e7ades.jpg|thumb|220px|Reconstructed fa\u00e7ades near Macedonia Square]]\n\nThe Skopje 2014 project also includes plans to transform the fa\u00e7ades of existing buildings in central Skopje into the neoclassical style. This includes the following buildings:\n\n*Buildings along Dimitrija \u010cupovski Street<ref name=\"build.mk5\">{{cite news|url=http://www.build.mk/?p=13047|title=\u0426\u0435\u043b\u0438\u043e\u0442 \u0441\u0442\u0440\u043e\u0433 \u0446\u0435\u043d\u0442\u0430\u0440 \u043d\u0430 \u0421\u043a\u043e\u043f\u0458\u0435 \u045c\u0435 \u0434\u043e\u0431\u0438\u0435 \u043d\u043e\u0432\u0438 \u0444\u0430\u0441\u0430\u0434\u0438|date=6 March 2012|publisher=build.mk|language=Macedonian|accessdate=5 July 2012|location=Skopje}}</ref>\n*Buildings along Macedonia Street<ref name=\"build.mk5\" />\n*Buildings along Nikola Vapcarov Street<ref name=\"build.mk5\" />\n*Buildings around Macedonia Square<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.build.mk/?p=14739|title=\u041f\u0440\u043e\u0434\u043e\u043b\u0436\u0443\u0432\u0430 \u043f\u0440\u043e\u043c\u0435\u043d\u0430\u0442\u0430 \u043d\u0430 \u0444\u0430\u0441\u0430\u0434\u0438\u0442\u0435 \u043e\u043a\u043e\u043b\u0443 \u041f\u043b\u043e\u0448\u0442\u0430\u0434\u043e\u0442 \u041c\u0430\u043a\u0435\u0434\u043e\u043d\u0438\u0458\u0430|date=3 May 2012|publisher=build.mk|language=Macedonian|accessdate=5 July 2012|location=Skopje}}</ref>\n*City Trade Center<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.build.mk/?p=15922|title=\u0413\u0422\u0426 \u045c\u0435 \u0434\u043e\u0431\u0438\u0435 \u043d\u043e\u0432\u0430 \u0444\u0430\u0441\u0430\u0434\u0430 \u0438 \u043d\u0430\u0434\u0433\u0440\u0430\u0434\u0431\u0430|date=14 June 2012|publisher=build.mk|language=Macedonian|accessdate=5 July 2012|location=Skopje}}</ref>\n*Department of Transport and Communications Building, located on Karpo\u0161's Rebellion Square.<ref name=\"http\">{{cite news|url=http://www.build.mk/?p=8540|title=\u041f\u043e\u0447\u043d\u0443\u0432\u0430 \u0443\u0440\u0435\u0434\u0443\u0432\u0430\u045a\u0435\u0442\u043e \u043d\u0430 \u043f\u043b\u043e\u0448\u0442\u0430\u0434\u043e\u0442 \u041a\u0430\u0440\u043f\u043e\u0448\u043e\u0432\u043e \u0432\u043e\u0441\u0442\u0430\u043d\u0438\u0435|publisher=build.mk|language=Macedonian|accessdate=28 June 2012|location=Skopje}}</ref>\n*[[Government of the Republic of Macedonia]] building. The new fa\u00e7ade appearance choice for this building was made by the Macedonian public through online votes on the government's website. There were five choices and the neoclassical choice won a plurality.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.build.mk/?p=13541|title=\u0412\u043e \u043c\u0430\u0458 \u043f\u0440\u043e\u0435\u043a\u0442, \u0430 \u043b\u0435\u0442\u043e\u0432\u043e \u0438 \u0442\u0435\u043d\u0434\u0435\u0440 \u0437\u0430 \u043c\u0435\u043d\u0443\u0432\u0430\u045a\u0435 \u043d\u0430 \u043b\u0438\u043a\u043e\u0442 \u043d\u0430 \u0432\u043b\u0430\u0434\u0438\u043d\u0430\u0442\u0430 \u0437\u0433\u0440\u0430\u0434\u0430|date=22 March 2012|publisher=build.mk|language=Macedonian|accessdate=5 July 2012|location=Skopje}}</ref>\n*MEPSO Building, located north of Macedonia Square.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.build.mk/?p=12950|title=\u0418 \u0433\u043b\u0430\u0432\u043d\u0430\u0442\u0430 \u0437\u0433\u0440\u0430\u0434\u0430 \u043d\u0430 \u041c\u0415\u041f\u0421\u041e \u0441\u043e \u043a\u043b\u0430\u0441\u0438\u0446\u0438\u0441\u0442\u0438\u0447\u043a\u0430 \u0444\u0430\u0441\u0430\u0434\u0430|date=2 March 2012|publisher=build.mk|language=Macedonian|accessdate=5 July 2012|location=Skopje}}</ref>\n*Ministry of Justice building<ref name=\"Vasilevski 2\">{{cite news|url=http://architect.mk/konkursi/824-konkurs-rekonstrukcija-i-adaptacija-za-objekt-upravna-zgrada-na-ministerstvo-za-pravda-skopje|title=\u041a\u043e\u043d\u043a\u0443\u0440\u0441 - \u0420\u0435\u043a\u043e\u043d\u0441\u0442\u0440\u0443\u043a\u0446\u0438\u0458\u0430 \u0438 \u0430\u0434\u0430\u043f\u0442\u0430\u0446\u0438\u0458\u0430 \u043d\u0430 \u0444\u0430\u0441\u0430\u0434\u0430 \u0437\u0430 \u043e\u0431\u0458\u0435\u043a\u0442 \u0423\u043f\u0440\u0430\u0432\u043d\u0430 \u0437\u0433\u0440\u0430\u0434\u0430 \u043d\u0430 \u041c\u0438\u043d\u0438\u0441\u0442\u0435\u0440\u0441\u0442\u0432\u043e \u0437\u0430 \u043f\u0440\u0430\u0432\u0434\u0430 \u0432\u043e \u0421\u043a\u043e\u043f\u0458\u0435|last=Vasilevski|first=Igor|date=3 August 2010|publisher=Architect.mk|language=Macedonian|accessdate=5 July 2012}}</ref>\n*[[Parliament of the Republic of Macedonia|Parliament]] building. The renovation of the Parliament also includes the construction of cupolas atop the building.<ref name=\"Smilevska\">{{cite news|url=http://vesti.alfa.mk/default.aspx?mid=36&eventid=9125|title=\u041e\u0442\u0432\u043e\u0440\u0435\u043d\u0438 \u0442\u0435\u043d\u0434\u0435\u0440\u0438\u0442\u0435 \u0437\u0430 \u0440\u0435\u043a\u043e\u043d\u0441\u0442\u0440\u0443\u043a\u0446\u0438\u0458\u0430 \u043d\u0430 \u0421\u043e\u0431\u0440\u0430\u043d\u0438\u0435\u0442\u043e|last=Smilevska|first=Milka|date=15 June 2009|publisher=Alfa TV|language=Macedonian|accessdate=5 July 2012|location=Skopje}}</ref>\n\n===Government buildings===\nThe following are new buildings being constructed to house various governmental functions.\n\n====Agency for Electronic Communications====\n[[File:Skopje 2014 - Agency for Electronic Communications and Archeological Museum.JPG|thumb|Agency for Electronic Communications (right)]]\nThe cornerstone for the new building to house the Agency for Electronic Communications was laid on 30 March 2011. It is being constructed on the eastern bank of the Vardar in between two other Skopje 2014 buildings, the Museum of Archaeology and the Financial Police Building.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.build.mk/?p=7083|title=\u041a\u0430\u043c\u0435\u043d \u0442\u0435\u043c\u0435\u043b\u043d\u0438\u043a \u0437\u0430 \u043d\u043e\u0432\u0438\u043e\u0442 \u043e\u0431\u0458\u0435\u043a\u0442 \u043d\u0430 \u0410\u0415\u041a|date=30 March 2011|publisher=build.mk|language=Macedonian|accessdate=2 July 2012|location=Skopje}}</ref>\n\nThe total cost of the building's construction is around 8.5 million euros, which the government claims will be fully funded by the Agency's budget. It is expected to be completed in 15 months or by the late summer of 2012.<ref name=\"Jovanova\">{{cite news|url=http://www.kapital.mk/MK/dneven_vesnik.aspx/26429/agencijata_za_elektronski_komunikacii_ja_dobiva_svojata_zgrada.aspx?iId=33|archive-url=https://archive.is/20130221020103/http://www.kapital.mk/MK/dneven_vesnik.aspx/26429/agencijata_za_elektronski_komunikacii_ja_dobiva_svojata_zgrada.aspx?iId=33|url-status=dead|archive-date=21 February 2013|title=\u0410\u0413\u0415\u041d\u0426\u0418\u0408\u0410\u0422\u0410 \u0417\u0410 \u0415\u041b\u0415\u041a\u0422\u0420\u041e\u041d\u0421\u041a\u0418 \u041a\u041e\u041c\u0423\u041d\u0418\u041a\u0410\u0426\u0418\u0418 \u0408\u0410 \u0414\u041e\u0411\u0418\u0412\u0410 \u0421\u0412\u041e\u0408\u0410\u0422\u0410 \u0417\u0413\u0420\u0410\u0414\u0410|last=Jovanova|first=Sonja|date=30 March 2011|publisher=Kapital|language=Macedonian|accessdate=2 July 2012|location=Skopje}}</ref>\n\n====Criminal Court Building====\nA new Criminal Court Building is being constructed as part of the project. The cornerstone for the building was laid on 25 May 2010. The building, 10 stories tall, has been topped out. In it will be 74 judicial offices, 22 high courts, and 2 large courtrooms. The 2-story basement will contain parking. The building, reported to cost 8.3 million euros, was planned to be completed after 18 months of construction.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.build.mk/?p=3626|title=\u041f\u043e\u0441\u0442\u0430\u0432\u0435\u043d \u043a\u0430\u043c\u0435\u043d \u0442\u0435\u043c\u0435\u043b\u043d\u0438\u043a \u0437\u0430 \u043d\u043e\u0432\u0438\u043e\u0442 \u041a\u0440\u0438\u0432\u0438\u0447\u0435\u043d \u0441\u0443\u0434|date=29 May 2010|publisher=build.mk|language=Macedonian|accessdate=3 July 2012|location=Skopje}}</ref>\n\n====Financial Police Building====\n[[File:MFAandFinancialPoliceBldgSkopje.jpg|220px|thumb|The completed Financial Police and Ministry of Foreign Affairs buildings]]\nOn 11 October 2010 the cornerstone for the new building to house the Financial Police of the Republic of Macedonia was laid. The site is located between the new Ministry of Foreign Affairs and the new Agency for Electronic Communications. The building, currently several months from completion, is cylindrical in shape and is capped by a dome-shaped roof. The total cost of construction will be roughly 13 million euros.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.build.mk/?p=5216|title=\u041a\u0430\u043c\u0435\u043d \u0442\u0435\u043c\u0435\u043b\u043d\u0438\u043a \u0437\u0430 \u0437\u0433\u0440\u0430\u0434\u0430 \u043d\u0430 \u041e\u0431\u0432\u0438\u043d\u0438\u0442\u0435\u043b\u0441\u0442\u0432\u043e\u0442\u043e \u0438 \u0424\u0438\u043d\u0430\u043d\u0441\u0438\u0441\u043a\u0430\u0442\u0430 \u043f\u043e\u043b\u0438\u0446\u0438\u0458\u0430|publisher=build.mk|language=Macedonian|accessdate=4 July 2012|location=Skopje}}</ref>\n\n====Ministry of Finance====\nThe government, in March 2011, invested 8.9 million euros into transforming an abandoned uncompleted building in central Skopje into a new home for the Ministry of Finance. Like the other governmental buildings in Skopje 2014, it will have a neoclassical appearance. Though it was scheduled to be completed in the first quarter of 2012, the building remains far from completion.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.build.mk/?p=6871|title=\u041c\u0438\u043d\u0438\u0441\u0442\u0435\u0440\u0441\u0442\u0432\u043e\u0442\u043e \u0437\u0430 \u0444\u0438\u043d\u0430\u043d\u0441\u0438\u0438 \u045c\u0435 \u0441\u0435 \u0441\u0435\u043b\u0438 \u0432\u043e \"\u0408\u0443\u0433\u043e\u0431\u0430\u043d\u043a\u0430\"|date=8 March 2011|publisher=build.mk|language=Macedonian|accessdate=4 July 2012|location=Skopje}}</ref>\n\n====Ministry of Foreign Affairs====\nConstruction of the new Ministry of Foreign Affairs building began in January 2010. It is located on the eastern bank of the Vardar between the Financial Police Building and Stiv Naumov Street. It will have two basement levels, seven above-ground levels, and a terrace atop the building. The building, which is nearly complete on the exterior, stands at a height of 27&nbsp;m (88.6&nbsp;ft) and will have costed 13.5 million euros when completed.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.build.mk/?p=2837|title=\u041e\u0444\u0438\u0446\u0438\u0458\u0430\u043b\u0435\u043d \u043a\u0430\u043c\u0435\u043d \u0442\u0435\u043c\u0435\u043b\u043d\u0438\u043a \u0437\u0430 \u043d\u043e\u0432\u043e\u0442\u043e \u041c\u041d\u0420|publisher=build.mk|language=Macedonian|accessdate=4 July 2012|location=Skopje}}</ref>\n\n====New City Hall====\nA new city hall for Skopje is being constructed below the [[Skopje Fortress|Kale Fortress]], on the eastern bank of the Vardar. It is being constructed, as most other buildings in the project, in the neoclassical style and will cost roughly 15 million euros. It will be 21&nbsp;m (68.9&nbsp;ft) tall, with six above-ground floors.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.build.mk/?p=7984|title=\u0421\u0435 \u0433\u0440\u0430\u0434\u0438 \u043e\u0431\u0458\u0435\u043a\u0442 \u0437\u0430 \u0441\u043a\u043e\u043f\u0441\u043a\u0430\u0442\u0430 \u0433\u0440\u0430\u0434\u0441\u043a\u0430 \u0430\u0434\u043c\u0438\u043d\u0438\u0441\u0442\u0440\u0430\u0446\u0438\u0458\u0430|date=3 June 2011|publisher=build.mk|language=Macedonian|accessdate=5 July 2012|location=Skopje}}</ref>\n\n====Old City Hall====\nAlthough a new city hall for Skopje is being constructed, the former one destroyed in the [[1963 Skopje earthquake]] will be fully reconstructed, as part of the Skopje 2014 project. It will be built on its original location at the north side of Macedonia Square, to the west of the Vardar Quay. A Greek investor will be building the Old City Hall, as well as a Marriott Hotel to the immediate left of the building, after purchasing the land in March 2011.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.build.mk/?p=6920|title=\u0413\u0440\u0447\u043a\u0438 \u0438\u043d\u0432\u0435\u0441\u0442\u0438\u0442\u043e\u0440 \u045c\u0435 \u0433\u0438 \u0433\u0440\u0430\u0434\u0438 \u041e\u0444\u0438\u0446\u0435\u0440\u0441\u043a\u0438\u043e\u0442 \u0434\u043e\u043c \u0438 \u0445\u043e\u0442\u0435\u043b\u043e\u0442 \u043d\u0430 \u041f\u043b\u043e\u0448\u0442\u0430\u0434 \u041c\u0430\u043a\u0435\u0434\u043e\u043d\u0438\u0458\u0430|date=12 March 2011|publisher=build.mk|language=Macedonian|accessdate=5 July 2012|location=Skopje}}</ref>\n\n====Water Management Building====\nAmong the buildings being constructed below the [[Skopje Fortress|Kale Fortress]] on the eastern bank of the Vardar is the Water Management Building. Construction of the building began in December 2011. It is expected to be completed in 3 years at a cost of 10 million euros.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.time.mk/read/58d92cc11d/d4bf718890/index.html|archive-url=https://archive.is/20130221032952/http://www.time.mk/read/58d92cc11d/d4bf718890/index.html|url-status=dead|archive-date=21 February 2013|title=\u041f\u043e\u0441\u0442\u0430\u0432\u0435\u043d \u043a\u0430\u043c\u0435\u043d-\u0442\u0435\u043c\u0435\u043b\u043d\u0438\u043a \u043d\u0430 \u043d\u043e\u0432\u0430\u0442\u0430 \u0437\u0433\u0440\u0430\u0434\u0430 \u043d\u0430 \u0408\u041f \"\u0412\u043e\u0434\u043e\u0432\u043e\u0434 \u0438 \u043a\u0430\u043d\u0430\u043b\u0438\u0437\u0430\u0446\u0438\u0458\u0430\"|date=4 December 2011|publisher=[[Macedonian Radio-Television]]|language=Macedonian|accessdate=5 July 2012|location=Skopje}}</ref><ref name=\"Trajkovska\">{{cite news|url=http://www.utrinski.com.mk/?ItemID=6C30BE3B498BB14E96CAE30F422EF3AF|archive-url=https://archive.is/20130219022739/http://www.utrinski.com.mk/?ItemID=6C30BE3B498BB14E96CAE30F422EF3AF|url-status=dead|archive-date=19 February 2013|title=\u0413\u0440\u0430\u0434\u0441\u043a\u0430\u0442\u0430 \u0430\u0434\u043c\u0438\u043d\u0438\u0441\u0442\u0440\u0430\u0446\u0438\u0458\u0430 \u045c\u0435 \u0434\u043e\u0431\u0438\u0435 \u0437\u0433\u0440\u0430\u0434\u0430 \u043f\u043e\u0434 \u041a\u0430\u043b\u0435|last=Trajkovska|first=Despina|date=13 December 2010|publisher=Utrinski Vesnik|language=Macedonian|accessdate=5 July 2012|location=Skopje}}</ref>\n\n===Monuments===\n\n====Justinian I====\n[[File:Justinian I . 2 . Monuments in Skopje.JPG|thumb|180px|Justinian I monument]]\n\nThe monument of [[Justinian I]], born in [[Tauresium]] just outside modern Skopje, arrived at Macedonia Square on June 16, 2011. Similar to the monument of Tsar Samuil, also on Macedonia Square, it consists of Justinian I sitting on a throne, which is placed on a pedestal. The monument is made of white marble with the exception of the bronze reliefs on the pedestal, also characteristics it shares with the Tsar Samuil monument. The pedestal is 3.5&nbsp;m (11.5&nbsp;ft) tall, while Justinian upon his throne measures a further 5&nbsp;m (16.4&nbsp;ft) in height.\n\nThe monument sits just north of the Stone Bridge, at the western bank of the Vardar River. It was made in Florence and cost over 1 million euros.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://sky.mk/component/content/article/1249-2011-06-17-11-56-48.html|title=\u0421\u0435 \u043f\u043e\u0441\u0442\u0430\u0432\u0443\u0432\u0430 \u0408\u0443\u0441\u0442\u0438\u043d\u0438\u0458\u0430\u043d \u041f\u0440\u0432\u0438|date=17 June 2011 <!--13:55-->|publisher=Sky.mk|language=Macedonian|accessdate=2011-06-18|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140203085300/http://sky.mk/component/content/article/1249-2011-06-17-11-56-48.html|archivedate=3 February 2014|df=}}</ref>\n\nSculpted by hand in the [[Pietro Bazzanti e Figlio Art Gallery|Bazzanti Art Gallery]] marble Studio of [[Florence]].\n\n====Mother Teresa====\nThe construction of a monument consisting of a statue of Skopje native [[Mother Teresa]] and a fountain is planned. The monument will be located near the MEPSO building, which is north of Macedonia Square near the Vardar Quay, though location on the roundabout near the Goce Del\u010dev Bridge is also a possibility. It is planned to stand around 30&nbsp;m (98.4&nbsp;ft) in height, even taller than the Warrior on a Horse monument.\n\nIt has been reported that a donation from India will fund the construction of the new Mother Teresa monument, who is already memorialized in the city with the [[Memorial House of Mother Teresa]] and a plaque marking the spot of her birth.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://bukvar.mk/news/kje-se-gradi-spomenik-na-majka-tereza-povisok-od-voinot-na-konj?newsid=9SxW|title=\u040c\u0415 \u0421\u0415 \u0413\u0420\u0410\u0414\u0418 \u0421\u041f\u041e\u041c\u0415\u041d\u0418\u041a \u041d\u0410 \u041c\u0410\u0408\u041a\u0410 \u0422\u0415\u0420\u0415\u0417\u0410 \u041f\u041e\u0412\u0418\u0421\u041e\u041a \u041e\u0414 \u0412\u041e\u0418\u041d\u041e\u0422 \u041d\u0410 \u041a\u041e\u040a|date=29 June 2012|publisher=Fakulteti.mk|language=Macedonian|accessdate=30 June 2012|location=Skopje}}</ref>\n\n====Pavilion at Macedonia Square====\n[[File:\u041b\u0435\u0442\u043d\u0438\u043a\u043e\u0432\u0435\u0446\u043e\u0442 \u043d\u0430 \u041f\u043b\u043e\u0448\u0442\u0430\u0434 (8).JPG|thumb|left|200px|The Pavilion at Macedonia Square]]\n\nThe Pavilion at Macedonia Square is situated on the north side of Macedonia Square. Construction began in early 2011 and was completed later that year at a cost of 350,000 euros.<ref name=\"Dimitrievski\">{{cite news|url=http://daily.mk/i-letnikovec?forward=567090|title=\u0418 \u043b\u0435\u0442\u043d\u0438\u043a\u043e\u0432\u0435\u0446 ...|last=Dimitrievski|first=Aleksandar|date=26 January 2011|publisher=Alfa TV|language=Macedonian|accessdate=23 June 2012|location=Skopje}}</ref> The pavilion consists of a dome supported by several columns, covering a statue of a romantic couple.\n\n====Porta Macedonia====\n[[File:Porta Macedonia, Skopie, Macedonia del Norte, 2014-04-16, DD 105.jpg|thumb|220px|[[Porta Macedonia]]]]\n{{Main|Porta Macedonia}}\n\nOne of the main symbols of the project is Porta Macedonia, a [[triumphal arch]] situated on 11 October Street, near Macedonia Square. The arch is meant to commemorate the long struggle for Macedonian independence. It is 21&nbsp;m (68.9&nbsp;ft) tall and contains 32 reliefs carved on the outside, depicting events from pre-history to the independence of the Republic of Macedonia. The inside of the arch consists of two levels, in which a souvenir shop and a gallery are located, and a rooftop observation deck. It formally opened to the public on Christmas Eve, January 6, 2012. The construction of Porta Macedonia is estimated at 4.5 million euros.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.build.mk/?p=11623|title=\"\u041f\u043e\u0440\u0442\u0430 \u041c\u0430\u043a\u0435\u0434\u043e\u043d\u0438\u0458\u0430\" \u0441\u0432\u0435\u0447\u0435\u043d\u043e \u043f\u0440\u0435\u0442\u0441\u0442\u0430\u0432\u0435\u043d\u0430 \u043d\u0430 \u0458\u0430\u0432\u043d\u043e\u0441\u0442\u0430|date=January 6, 2012|publisher=build.mk|language=Macedonian|accessdate=22 June 2012|location=Skopje}}</ref>\n\n====Tsar Samuil====\n[[File:Samuil 1. Monuments in Skopje.JPG|thumb|left|180px|Tsar Samuil monument]]\n\nThe monument to [[Samuel of Bulgaria]] is among the new focal points of Macedonia Square. Officially unveiled on 28 June 2011, it is situated in front of the Pelister building, to the right of where Macedonia Street meets Macedonia Square.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.a1.com.mk/vesti/default.aspx?VestID=139834|title=\u041f\u043e\u0441\u0442\u0430\u0432\u0435\u043d \u0441\u043f\u043e\u043c\u0435\u043d\u0438\u043a\u043e\u0442 \u043d\u0430 \u0426\u0430\u0440 \u0421\u0430\u043c\u043e\u0438\u043b|date=2011-06-28 <!--  15:23 --> |publisher=\u04101|language=Macedonian|accessdate=2011-07-31}}</ref>\n\nThe monument, mostly in white marble, consists of a depiction of Tsar Samuil sitting on a throne, totaling 5&nbsp;m (16.4&nbsp;ft) in height, and is placed on a pedestal which itself is a further 3.5&nbsp;m (11.5&nbsp;ft) tall. The reliefs on the sides of the pedestal are bronze.  Tsar Samuil, in the monument, holds a scepter. Made in [[Florence]], sculpted by hand in the [[Pietro Bazzanti e Figlio Art Gallery|Bazzanti Art Gallery]] marble Studio, the total cost of the Tsar Samuil monument was roughly 3.5 million euros.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.dnevnik.com.mk/default.asp?ItemID=E96A2FA4FAECB34697607E35AE088F1A|archive-url=https://archive.is/20130219045443/http://www.dnevnik.com.mk/default.asp?ItemID=E96A2FA4FAECB34697607E35AE088F1A|url-status=dead|archive-date=2013-02-19|title=\u0421\u043f\u043e\u043c\u0435\u043d\u0438\u043a\u043e\u0442 \u043d\u0430 \u0426\u0430\u0440 \u0421\u0430\u043c\u043e\u0438\u043b \u0441\u0442\u0438\u0433\u043d\u0430 \u043d\u0430 \u043f\u043b\u043e\u0448\u0442\u0430\u0434\u043e\u0442 \"\u041c\u0430\u043a\u0435\u0434\u043e\u043d\u0438\u0458\u0430\"|date=2011-06-28 <!-- , 11:11 -->|publisher=Dnevnik|language=Macedonian|accessdate=2011-07-31}}</ref>\n\nThe [[fringe theory]]  Samuil being the first Tsar of the Macedonian Slavs is held mainly in the Republic of Macedonia.<ref>An outline of Macedonian history from ancient times to 1991. Macedonian Embassy London. Retrieved on 2007-04-28.</ref> This view is ahistorical, as it projects modern ethnic distinctions into the past.<ref>The Oxford Dictionary of Byzantium, Vol 1, New York-Oxford, Oxford University Press, 1991 (p. 1838)</ref>\n\n====Warrior monument====\n{{Multiple image\n | align     = right\n | direction = horizontal\n | width     = 150\n | image1    = Skopje - Warrior Monument.jpg\n | caption1  = \n | image2    = \u0412\u043e\u0438\u043d\u043e\u0442 \u0441\u043e \u0444\u043e\u043d\u0442\u0430\u043d\u0430 (6).JPG\n | footer    = Warrior monument\n}}\nOn the opposite side of the Stone Bridge from Macedonia Square is Karpo\u0161's Rebellion Square, which serves as a main entrance to the [[Old Bazaar, Skopje|Old Bazaar]]. It is undergoing a major reconstruction, as part of Skopje 2014, and its new centerpiece will be the statue and fountain officially named \"Warrior,\" though it is widely believed that the statue is a depiction of [[Philip II of Macedon]], not to be confused with the equestrian statue of Philip II in Skopje's Avtokomanda neighborhood. The statue was placed onto the square on 22 May 2012.\n\nMade in Vicenza, the statue is 15&nbsp;m (49.2&nbsp;ft) tall and is placed on a 13&nbsp;m (42.7&nbsp;ft) tall pedestal. The entire monument will cost roughly 2 million euros.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.build.mk/?p=15338|title=\u0424\u0438\u043b\u0438\u043f \u0412\u0442\u043e\u0440\u0438 \u043f\u043e\u0441\u0442\u0430\u0432\u0435\u043d \u043d\u0430 \u043f\u043b\u043e\u0448\u0442\u0430\u0434\u043e\u0442 \"\u041a\u0430\u0440\u043f\u043e\u0448\u043e\u0432\u043e \u0432\u043e\u0441\u0442\u0430\u043d\u0438\u0435\"|date=22 May 2012|publisher=build.mk|language=Macedonian|accessdate=29 June 2012|location=Skopje}}</ref> \n\n====Warrior on a Horse monument====\n{{Multiple image\n | align     = left\n | direction = horizontal\n | width     = 150\n | image1    = Aleksandar Makedonski vo Skopje 011.jpg\n | caption1  = \n | image2    = Guerrero a caballo, Skopie, Macedonia, 2014-04-17, DD 103.JPG\n | footer    = Warrior on a Horse monument\n}}\nPerhaps the main symbol of the Skopje 2014 project is the Warrior on a Horse ({{lang-mk|\u0412\u043e\u0438\u043d \u043d\u0430 \u043a\u043e\u045a}}) statue and fountain in the centre of Macedonia Square. It is typically thought to depict [[Alexander the Great]], though it is not officially named for him.<ref>[http://edition.cnn.com/2011/10/04/world/europe/macedonia-skopje-2014/index.html Is Macedonia's capital being turned into a theme park?] CNN International, 10 October 2011</ref><ref>[https://www.theguardian.com/world/2011/aug/14/alexander-great-macedonia-warrior-horse Macedonia statue: Alexander the Great or a warrior on a horse?] The Guardian, Sunday 14 August 2011</ref><ref>https://www.citylab.com/design/2013/08/skopjes-strange-quest-rewrite-its-history-through-public-sculpture/6416/</ref>\n\nThe statue was sculpted by [[Valentina Stevanovska]] and cast in bronze with lost wax casting technique in the [[Ferdinando Marinelli Artistic Foundry]] of [[Florence]].\n\n\"Alexander\" was officially completed on September 8, 2011 to commemorate 20 years of the independence of the Republic of Macedonia. It is 14.5&nbsp;m (47.6&nbsp;ft) tall and it sits on a cylindrical column, which itself is 10&nbsp;m (32.8&nbsp;ft) in height. The column consists of three large ivory sections, each separated by a thinner bronze ring. Each section contains reliefs. The column stands in a fountain. At the base of the column are 8 bronze soldiers, each 3&nbsp;m (9.8&nbsp;ft) tall. There are also 8 bronze lions, each 2.5&nbsp;m (8.3&nbsp;ft) tall, around the edges of the fountain pool, four of which act as part of the fountain, releasing water from their mouths. The fountain also plays music.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://vesti.alfa.mk/default.aspx?mid=36&eventid=40603|title=\u041f\u0443\u0448\u0442\u0430\u045a\u0435 \u0432\u043e \u0443\u043f\u043e\u0442\u0440\u0435\u0431\u0430 \u0444\u043e\u043d\u0442\u0430\u043d\u0430 \u0441\u043e \u0441\u043f\u043e\u043c\u0435\u043d\u0438\u043a\u043e\u0442 \"\u0412\u043e\u0438\u043d \u043d\u0430 \u043a\u043e\u045a\"|date=8 September 2011|publisher=Alfa TV|language=Macedonian|accessdate=23 June 2012|location=Skopje|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120723123128/http://vesti.alfa.mk/default.aspx?mid=36&eventid=40603|archivedate=23 July 2012|df=}}</ref>\n\nThe total cost of the Warrior on a Horse monument is roughly 7.5 million euros.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.trtmacedonian.com/trtworld/mk/newsDetail.aspx?HaberKodu=a7c635ff-8af9-489b-867a-9d01e3251863|title=\u041f\u041e\u0421\u0422\u0410\u0412\u0415\u041d \u0421\u041f\u041e\u041c\u0415\u041d\u0418\u041a\u041e\u0422 \u041d\u0410 \u0410\u041b\u0415\u041a\u0421\u0410\u041d\u0414\u0410\u0420 \u041c\u0410\u041a\u0415\u0414\u041e\u041d\u0421\u041a\u0418 \u041d\u0410\u0420\u0415\u0427\u0415\u041d \"\u0412\u041e\u0418\u041d \u041d\u0410 \u041a\u041e\u040a\" \u0412\u041e \u0421\u041a\u041e\u041f\u0408\u0415|publisher=www.trtmacedonian.com|accessdate=20 September 2011}}</ref>\n\n====Other monuments====\nAside from the major monuments in the Skopje 2014 above, many other ones have been erected, or are planned to be erected in the city. These include the following:\n\n<center>\n{|class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|- class=\"hintergrundfarbe5\"\n! Person/group<br>depicted\n! Estimated<br>cost (\u20ac)\n! Location\n! Reference\n! Image\n|-\n| [[Nexhat Agolli]]\n| \n| Kej 13-ti Noemvri, in front of Makedonski Telekom headquarters\n| <center><ref name=\"build.mk3\" /></center>\n| [[File:Statue of Nexhat Agolli.jpg|100px]]\n|-\n| [[Todor Aleksandrov]]\n| 350,000\n| \u010ce\u0161ma Park, [[Municipality of Kisela Voda (Skopje)|Municipality of Kisela Voda]]\n| <center><ref name=\"Jakovleski\">{{cite news|url=http://www.telma.com.mk/index.php?task=content&cat=1&rub=15&item=17988|title=\u0422\u041e\u0414\u041e\u0420 \u0410\u041b\u0415\u041a\u0421\u0410\u041d\u0414\u0420\u041e\u0412 \"\u0414\u041e\u0408\u0410\u0412\u0410\" \u0412\u041e \u041a\u0418\u0421\u0415\u041b\u0410 \u0412\u041e\u0414\u0410|last=Jakovleski|first=Martin|date=26 June 2012|publisher=Telma|language=Macedonian|accessdate=27 June 2012|location=Skopje}}</ref><ref>[http://www.utrinski.com.mk/default.asp?ItemID=6414F07615A6DE46A1B478C33E80BB27 \u0423\u0442\u0440\u0438\u043d\u0441\u043a\u0438 \u0432\u0435\u0441\u0442\u0438\u043a, 18.10.2012, \u201e\u0412\u043e\u0458\u0432\u043e\u0434\u0430\u0442\u0430 \u043d\u0430 \u043a\u043e\u045a\u201c \u0438 \u043e\u0444\u0438\u0446\u0438\u0458\u0430\u043b\u043d\u043e \u0422\u043e\u0434\u043e\u0440 \u0410\u043b\u0435\u043a\u0441\u0430\u043d\u0434\u0440\u043e\u0432.] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121022051851/http://www.utrinski.com.mk/default.asp?ItemID=6414F07615A6DE46A1B478C33E80BB27 |date=2012-10-22 }}</ref></center>\n|\n|-\n| [[Metodija Andonov-\u010cento]]\n| 800,000\n| [[Macedonia Square, Skopje|Macedonia Square]], in front of Trend building\n| <center><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.utrinski.com.mk/default.asp?ItemID=EB2E0B9EAFF64240892435D1973BEF20|archive-url=https://archive.is/20130219042247/http://www.utrinski.com.mk/default.asp?ItemID=EB2E0B9EAFF64240892435D1973BEF20|url-status=dead|archive-date=February 19, 2013|title=\u0427\u0435\u043d\u0442\u043e \u0441\u0435 \u0438\u0441\u043f\u0440\u0430\u0432\u0438 \u043f\u0440\u0435\u0434 \"\u0422\u0440\u0435\u043d\u0434\"|last=T|first=Ds|date=June 7, 2010|publisher=Utrinski Vesnik|language=Macedonian|accessdate=25 June 2012|location=Skopje}}</ref></center>\n| [[File:Cento monument on Macedonian National holiday Ilinden - 2 Aug 2010.JPG|100px]]\n|-\n| [[ASNOM]]\n| 1.9 million\n| \u017dena Borec Park, across 11 October Street from 