toman Empire: Breaking New Ground'' (Plenum/Kluwer Academic Press, 2000)\n* Barkey, Karen. ''Empire of Difference: The Ottomans in Comparative Perspective.'' (2008) 357pp [https://www.amazon.com/Empire-Difference-Ottomans-Comparative-Perspective/dp/0521715334/ref=sr_1_7?ie=UTF8&s=books&qid=1240307430&sr=1-7 Amazon.com], excerpt and text search\n* Davison, Roderic H. ''Reform in the Ottoman Empire, 1856\u20131876'' (New York: Gordian Press, 1973)\n* Deringil, Selim. ''The well-protected domains: ideology and the legitimation of power in the Ottoman Empire, 1876\u20131909'' (London: IB Tauris, 1998)\n* Findley, Carter V. ''Bureaucratic Reform in the Ottoman Empire: The Sublime Porte, 1789\u20131922'' (Princeton University Press, 1980)\n* [[Suraiya Faroqhi|Faroqhi, Suraiya]]. ''The Ottoman Empire: A Short History'' (2009) 196pp\n* McMeekin, Sean. ''The Berlin-Baghdad Express: The Ottoman Empire and Germany's Bid for World Power'' (2010)\n* Nicolle, David. ''Armies of the Ottoman Turks 1300\u20131774'' (Osprey Publishing, 1983)\n* Palmer, Alan. ''The Decline and Fall of the Ottoman Empire''. (New York: Barnes and Noble, 1992) 306 p., maps. {{ISBN|0-87131-754-0}}\n* Pamuk, Sevket. ''A Monetary History of the Ottoman Empire'' (1999). pp.&nbsp;276\n* Stone, Norman \"Turkey in the Russian Mirror\" pp.&nbsp;86\u2013100 from ''Russia War, Peace and Diplomacy'' edited by Mark & Ljubica Erickson, Weidenfeld & Nicolson: London, 2004 {{ISBN|0-297-84913-1}}.\n* {{cite book |last1=Uyar |first1=Mesut |last2=Erickson |first2=Edward |title=A Military History of the Ottomans: From Osman to Atat\u00fcrk |year=2009 |isbn=978-0-275-98876-0}}\n\n===Historiography===\n* Aksan, Virginia H. \"What's Up in Ottoman Studies?\" ''Journal of the Ottoman and Turkish Studies Association'' 1.1-2 (2014): 3-21. [https://www.jstor.org/stable/10.2979/jottturstuass.1.1-2.3 online]\n** [https://www.jstor.org/stable/10.2979/jottturstuass.2.1.215 comment by Ehud R. Toledano]  and  [https://muse.jhu.edu/article/745216/summary  reply by Aksan] \n* Finkel, Caroline. \"Ottoman history: whose history is it?.\" ''International Journal of Turkish Studies'' 14.1/2 (2008).\n* Hartmann, Daniel Andreas. \"Neo-Ottomanism: The Emergence and Utility of a New Narrative on Politics, Religion, Society, and History in Turkey\" (Ph.D. Dissertation, Central European University, 2013) [http://www.etd.ceu.hu/2013/hartmann_daniel.pdf online].\n* Eissenstat, Howard. \"Children of \u00d6zal: The New Face of Turkish Studies\" ''Journal of the Ottoman and Turkish Studies Association'' 1#1 (2014), pp. 23-35 DOI: 10.2979/jottturstuass.1.1-2.23 [https://www.jstor.org/stable/10.2979/jottturstuass.1.1-2.23 online]\n* {{Cite journal|last=Kayal\u0131|first=Hasan|date=December 2017|title=The Ottoman Experience of World War I: Historiographical Problems and Trends|journal=The Journal of Modern History|language=en|volume=89|issue=4|pages=875\u2013907|doi=10.1086/694391|issn=0022-2801}}\n* Lieven, Dominic. ''Empire: The Russian Empire and its rivals'' (Yale UP, 2002), comparisons with Russian, British, & Habsburg empires. [https://www.amazon.com/Empire-Russian-Its-Rivals/dp/0300097263/ excerpt]\n* Mikhail, Alan; Philliou, Christine M. \"The Ottoman Empire and the Imperial Turn,\" ''Comparative Studies in Society & History'' (2012) 54#4 pp.&nbsp;721\u201345. Comparing the Ottomans to other empires opens new insights about the dynamics of imperial rule, periodization, and political transformation\n* Olson, Robert, \"Ottoman Empire\" in {{cite book|editor=Kelly Boyd|title=Encyclopedia of Historians and Historical Writing vol 2|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=0121vD9STIMC&pg=PA892|year=1999|publisher=Taylor & Francis|pages=892\u201396|isbn=978-1-884964-33-6}}\n* Quataert, Donald. \"Ottoman History Writing and Changing Attitudes towards the Notion of 'Decline.'\" ''History Compass'' 1 (2003): 1\u20139.\n* Y\u0131lmaz, Yasir. \"Nebulous Ottomans vs. Good Old Habsburgs: A Historiographical Comparison.\" ''Austrian History Yearbook'' 48 (2017): 173-190. [https://www.academia.edu/download/52736768/Yilmaz__Yasir__-_nebulous_ottomans_vs_good_old_habsburgs_a_historiographical_comparison.pdf Online]\n{{refend}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{Spoken Wikipedia-2|2008-03-29|Wikipedia - Ottoman Empire - Main History.ogg|Wikipedia - Ottoman Empire - Part 2.ogg}}\n{{Sister project links |wikt= |commons=Ottoman Empire |commonscat=yes|b=yes|voy=yes|v=yes|s=yes|d=yes|d-search=Q12560}}\n* [http://courses.washington.edu/otap/ Ottoman Text Archive Project \u2013 University of Washington]\n* [http://www.shapell.org/journeys.aspx?american-travelers-to-the-holy-land-in-the-19th-century American Travelers to the Holy Land in the 19th Century] Shapell Manuscript Foundation\n* [http://www.umich.edu/~turkish/ottemp.html The Ottoman Empire: Resources \u2013 University of Michigan]\n* [http://www.theottomans.org/ Information about Ottomans]\n* [http://www.wdl.org/en/item/11770/ Turkey in Asia], 1920\n\n{{Ottoman Empire topics}}\n{{Navboxes\n|list=\n{{Former Monarchies}}\n{{Turkic topics}}\n{{Turkey topics}}\n{{History of Anatolia}}\n{{Empires}}\n{{Medieval states in Anatolia}}\n{{History of Europe}}\n}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Ottoman Empire| ]]\n[[Category:Historical Turkic states]]\n[[Category:1299 establishments in Asia]]\n[[Category:1923 disestablishments in Asia]]\n[[Category:1923 disestablishments in Europe]]\n[[Category:Overseas empires]]\n[[Category:States and territories established in 1299]]\n[[Category:States and territories disestablished in 1922]]\n[[Category:States and territories disestablished in 1923]]\n[[Category:Former countries in the Middle East]]\n[[Category:Former countries in the Balkans]]\n[[Category:Former countries in Africa]]\n", "name_user": "72.12.216.168", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "(\u2192\u200eSports:None)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ottoman_Empire"}
{"title_page": "Jos\u00e9 P\u00e9kerman", "text_new": "{{spanish name|P\u00e9kerman|Krimen}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=May 2018}}\n{{Infobox football biography\n | name            = Jos\u00e9  Pokemon\n | image           = Jos\u00e9 N\u00e9stor P\u00e9kerman and Police at Colombia vs Uruguay match for Russia 2018 (cropped).jpg\n | caption         = P\u00e9kerman as [[Colombia national football team|Colombia]] manager in 2016\n | fullname        = Jos\u00e9 N\u00e9stor P\u00e9kerman Krimen<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.ecbloguer.com/capsulas/?p=52627 |title=C\u00e1psulas de f\u00fatbol \u00bb El segundo apellido de Pekerman es Krimen |publisher=Ecbloguer.com |date=22 February 1999 |accessdate=12 June 2014 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140707223843/http://www.ecbloguer.com/capsulas/?p=52627 |archive-date=7 July 2014 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n | height          = 1.76 m\n | birth_date      = {{birth date and age|1949|9|3|df=y}}\n | birth_place     = [[Villa Dom\u00ednguez]], Argentina\n | currentclub     = \n | position        = [[Midfielder]]\n | youthyears1     =            | youthclubs1 = [[Argentinos Juniors]]\n | years1          = 1970\u20131974  | caps1 = 134  | goals1 = 12  | clubs1 = [[Argentinos Juniors]]\n | years2          = 1974\u20131977  | caps2 = 101  | goals2 = 15  | clubs2 = [[Independiente Medell\u00edn]]\n | totalcaps       = 235 | totalgoals = 27\n | manageryears1   = 1981\u20131982  | managerclubs1 = [[Chacarita Juniors]] (youth)\n | manageryears2   = 1982\u20131992  | managerclubs2 = [[Argentinos Juniors]] (youth)\n | manageryears3   = 1992\u20131994  | managerclubs3 = [[Colo-Colo]] (youth)\n | manageryears4   = 1994\u20132001  | managerclubs4 = [[Argentina national under-20 football team|Argentina U20]]\n | manageryears5   = 2004\u20132006  | managerclubs5 = [[Argentina national football team|Argentina]]\n | manageryears6   = 2007\u20132008  | managerclubs6 = [[Club Toluca|Toluca]]\n | manageryears7   = 2009       | managerclubs7 = [[UANL Tigres|Tigres UANL]]\n | manageryears8   = 2012\u20132018  | managerclubs8 = [[Colombia national football team|Colombia]]\n}}\n'''Jos\u00e9 N\u00e9stor P\u00e9kerman Krimen''' ({{IPA-es|xo\u02c8se \u02c8pekerman}}; born 3 September 1949) is an Argentine-Colombian professional [[Association football|football]] coach and former manager of [[Colombia national football team|the Colombian national football team]]. As a youth level coach for Argentina, he won the [[FIFA World Youth Championship]] three times, and the U20 [[South American Youth Championship]] twice. He coached the [[Argentina national football team]] in the [[2006 FIFA World Cup]] and became coach of the [[Colombian national football team|Colombian national team]] in 2012. He subsequently managed the Colombian national team during the 2014 and 2018 FIFA World Cups where he led the team to their best result in 2014.\n\n==Player career==\n[[File:Jos\u00e9 Pekerman Deportivo Toluca 2007.jpg|thumb|Jos\u00e9 P\u00e9kerman in 2007]]\nP\u00e9kerman's career as a footballer was uneventful. A [[midfielder]], he played from 1970 to 1974 for [[Argentinos Juniors]] scoring 12 goals in 134 matches. He was transferred to [[Independiente Medell\u00edn]], in Colombia, where he scored 15 goals in 101 matches.\n\nHis player days ended at age 28 with a serious knee injury. P\u00e9kerman supported himself and his family with various odd jobs, including a stint as a taxi driver.{{CN|date=September 2019}}\n\n==Coaching career==\n===Youth coaching===\nBack in Argentina, P\u00e9kerman worked as a youth coach for [[Chacarita Juniors]] and then occupied the same position with [[Argentinos Juniors]]. He then moved to Chile to coach [[Colo-Colo]]'s youth divisions.\n\nIn 1994, he was offered to coach the Argentina national under-20 and under-17 sides by the [[Argentine Football Association]]. This caused some surprise as his [[r\u00e9sum\u00e9]] did not include any major achievements at this stage. He teamed up with [[Hugo Tocalli]] and coach Eduardo Urtasun.\n\nP\u00e9kerman's success, however, silenced the critics: his under-20 team won the [[FIFA World Youth Championship]] three times, [[1995 FIFA World Youth Championship|1995]] (Qatar), [[1997 FIFA World Youth Championship|1997]] (Malaysia), and [[2001 FIFA World Youth Championship|2001]] (Argentina), thus giving the names to his three pet dogs - Qatar, Malaysia and Argentina. The team also won the two [[South American Youth Championship]]s in 1997 and 1999.\n\nWhen the national coach [[Daniel Passarella]] resigned after the [[1998 FIFA World Cup|1998 World Cup]], P\u00e9kerman was offered his position. He declined, assuming instead the position of general manager of all national teams. [[Marcelo Bielsa]] was hired as coach on P\u00e9kerman's recommendation, and remained in charge until after Argentina's gold medal performance in the 2004 Summer Olympics.\n\nIn 2003, P\u00e9kerman moved to Spain at the behest of Argentine businessman [[Daniel Grinbank]], who had acquired [[Spanish Second Division]] side [[CD Legan\u00e9s]]. After a few months serving as director of football, the project crumbled and P\u00e9kerman left Spain.\n\nWhen Marcelo Bielsa resigned as coach, P\u00e9kerman was one of the two candidates for the coaching job, alongside [[Carlos Bianchi]], who had left [[Boca Juniors]] a few months earlier, and wanted to take a [[sabbatical|sabbatical year]] away from football.\n\n===World Cup 2006===\nOn 15 September 2004, P\u00e9kerman was named coach of the [[Argentina national football team]], which qualified for the [[2006 FIFA World Cup|2006 World Cup]]. The nation dominated its initial two group stage matches and drew with the [[Netherlands national football team|Netherlands]] in the third match, emerging on top of their group on goal difference. The ''Albicelestes'' then moved on to the round of 16, beating [[Mexico national football team|Mexico]] 2\u20131 [[overtime (sports)|after extra time]] in a comeback victory.\n\nIn the quarter-finals, Argentina went ahead 1\u20130 against hosts [[Germany national football team|Germany]], but shortly before the end of the match, Germany equalised through a [[Miroslav Klose]] header. Germany would go on to win on penalties, sending Argentina out of the tournament. P\u00e9kerman made defensive substitutions, including taking off [[Juan Rom\u00e1n Riquelme]] for [[Esteban Cambiasso]], and after the loss, announced his resignation. [[Argentine Football Association]] (AFA) President [[Julio Grondona]] tried to dissuade P\u00e9kerman from leaving, but it was later announced that [[Alfio Basile]], who had previously coached Argentina during the [[1994 FIFA World Cup|1994 World Cup]], would replace him as coach.\n\n===Post-World Cup===\nOn 30 May 2007, P\u00e9kerman resumed his coaching career, taking up the position of head coach of [[Club Toluca]] in Mexico, replacing fellow Argentine [[Am\u00e9rico Gallego]]. At the end of the [[Primera Divisi\u00f3n de M\u00e9xico Clausura 2008|Clausura 2008 tournament]], he was replaced by [[Jos\u00e9 Manuel de la Torre]].\n\nOn 23 February 2009, P\u00e9kerman was appointed as the head coach of [[UANL Tigres]] after the sacking of [[Manuel Lapuente]] following a series of bad results. After the end of [[2009 Primera Divisi\u00f3n de M\u00e9xico Clausura|Clausura 2009]], however, he was terminated and replaced by [[Daniel Guzm\u00e1n]].\n\nIn July 2010, it had been reported that P\u00e9kerman was in serious talks with the [[Australia national association football team|Australian national team]], as well as talks with the [[Japan national football team|Japanese national team]] about taking over the role as senior manager following the resignation of their managers.\n\n===2014 World Cup cycle and becoming coach of Colombia===\nIn January 2012, P\u00e9kerman became the new coach of the [[Colombian national football team|Colombian national team]], replacing ousted coach [[Leonel \u00c1lvarez (footballer, born 1965)|Leonel \u00c1lvarez]]. P\u00e9kerman was the third coach of the Colombian team during the South American World Cup qualifiers; before \u00c1lvarez, [[Hern\u00e1n Dar\u00edo G\u00f3mez]] was at the helm. For his first match, a friendly against Mexico, P\u00e9kerman impressed, with the Colombians completely taking control of the friendly in an eventual 2\u20130 victory. In his first [[2014 FIFA World Cup qualification (CONMEBOL)|qualifying]] match for the [[2014 FIFA World Cup|2014 World Cup]], a struggling Colombia managed to win 0\u20131 over [[Peru national football team|Peru]] in [[Lima]]. P\u00e9kerman, however, was criticized for using a long-range style of play rather than a close midfield passing control. This resulted in a weak Colombian side that lost to [[Ecuador national football team|Ecuador]] 1\u20130 away from home, his first loss.\n\nIn his home debut, P\u00e9kerman orchestrated an astonishing comeback as Colombia demolished [[2011 Copa Am\u00e9rica]] champions [[Uruguay national football team|Uruguay]] 4\u20130 in the seventh round of World Cup qualifiers. Under his direction, Colombia also won 1\u20133 away over [[Chile national football team|Chile]] and 2\u20130 over [[Paraguay national football team|Paraguay]] at home in [[Barranquilla]]. A few days later, P\u00e9kerman experimented without many star players such as [[Radamel Falcao]] and [[James Rodr\u00edguez]] against [[Cameroon national football team|Cameroon]], resulting in a comfortable 3\u20130 home victory. For the last match of 2012, Colombia drew 2014 World Cup hosts [[Brazil national football team|Brazil]] 1\u20131 despite missing two of the squad's star players.\n\nIn the opening match of 2013, P\u00e9kerman experimented yet again, this time against the [[Guatemala national football team|Guatemala]] side; he used only substitutes in a 4\u20131 victory, opting not to deploy senior stars, including Radamel Falcao. During the next round of qualifiers, P\u00e9kerman continued with the promising 4\u20132\u20132\u20132 formation that facilitated Colombia's comfortable defeat of [[Bolivia national football team|Bolivia]] in a 5\u20130 home victory. P\u00e9kerman, however, decided to use a different formation in the match, 4\u20134\u20131\u20131, which led to a shocking 1\u20130 away loss to neighbours [[Venezuela national football team|Venezuela]]. He was heavily criticized for experimenting with his side's formation, a loss that took the nation from second to third place in the qualifying table. In the match against his home nation Argentina, P\u00e9kerman changed the lineup and formation to better \"deal\" with the South American giants, which led to a hard-fought 0\u20130 draw. Despite this, P\u00e9kerman was again questioned with his lineup choices.<ref>{{cite web|author=Featured Columnist |url=http://bleacherreport.com/articles/1666131-argentina-vs-colombia-6-things-we-learned-from-world-cup-qualifer/page/5 |title=Argentina vs. Colombia: 6 Things We Learned from World Cup Qualifier |publisher=Bleacher Report |date=7 June 2013 |accessdate=12 June 2014}}</ref>\n\nAfter Colombia qualified for the 2014 World Cup after a 3\u20133 home draw against Chile, P\u00e9kerman expressed his joy for helping Colombia return to the World Cup for the first time in 16 years, considering it to be \"one of the greatest joys in his life.\"<ref>{{cite web|last=Diego |first=Juan |url=http://comutricolor.com/una-de-las-mayores-alegrias-de-mi-vida-pekerman/ |title=\"Es una de las mayores alegr\u00edas de mi vida\": Jos\u00e9 P\u00e9kerman |publisher=ComuTricolor.com |date= |accessdate=12 June 2014}}</ref> Following Colombia's qualification, P\u00e9kerman received Colombian citizenship from [[Juan Manuel Santos]], the [[president of Colombia]].<ref name=\"comutricolor1\">{{cite web|author=webmaster |url=http://comutricolor.com/jose-pekerman-nacionalidad-colombiana/ |title=Jos\u00e9 P\u00e9kerman ser\u00e1 nacionalizado colombiano |publisher=ComuTricolor.com |date= |accessdate=12 June 2014}}</ref>\n\nColombia won all three of its group matches (scoring nine goals and conceding only two) and went on to defeat Uruguay in the Round of 16 before losing to the host nation of Brazil in the quarter-finals. In August 2014, P\u00e9kerman extended his contract with Colombia until 2018.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.dailymail.co.uk/sport/football/article-2728906/Jose-Pekerman-signs-new-four-year-deal-stay-Colombia-manager.html|title=Pekerman signs new four-year deal to stay on as Colombia manager|work=Mail Online|access-date=12 October 2017}}</ref>\n\nFor the second consecutive time, P\u00e9kerman qualified Colombia for the [[FIFA World Cup]] this time for the [[2018 FIFA World Cup|2018 edition]] in Russia. Colombia suffered a controversial defeat in their first group stage game against a well organized and determined Japan, but then came out much stronger to inflict a 3-0 victory over Poland (effectively knocking them out of the tournament in the process). After beating Senegal 1-0 in the last game of the group stage, Colombia moved to the round of 16 as first in their group. After a bitter and contested match, Colombia lost on penalties to England.\n\n==Honours==\n===Manager===\n;Argentina U20\n*[[South American Youth Championship]]: [[1997 South American U-20 Championship|1997]], [[1999 South American U-20 Championship|1999]]; Runner-up [[1995 South American U-20 Championship|1995]], [[2001 South American U-20 Championship|2001]]\n*[[FIFA U-20 World Cup]]: [[1995 FIFA World Youth Championship|1995]], [[1997 FIFA World Youth Championship|1997]],  [[2001 FIFA World Youth Championship|2001]]\n\n;Argentina\n[[FIFA Confederations Cup]]: Runner-up [[2005 FIFA Confederations Cup|2005]]\n\n===Individual===\n* South American Coach of the Year (3): 2012, 2013, 2014 <ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.losandes.com.ar/notas/2014/1/1/jose-pekerman-mejor-sudamerica-759299.asp |title=Jos\u00e9 Pekerman, el mejor DT de Sudam\u00e9rica - M\u00e1s Deportes - Diario Los Andes |publisher=Losandes.com.ar |date= |accessdate=12 June 2014 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140405004221/http://losandes.com.ar/notas/2014/1/1/jose-pekerman-mejor-sudamerica-759299.asp |archive-date=5 April 2014 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n* IFFHS Best National Coach of the Year Nominee (1): 2013 (5th) <ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.goal.com/en-ke/news/4500/main/2014/01/28/4575364/scolari-named-among-elite-coaches |title=Scolari named among elite coaches |publisher=Goal.com |date=28 January 2014 |accessdate=12 June 2014}}</ref>\n\n==Management style and legacy==\nP\u00e9kerman is known for his tactical management style, often selecting the players that fit his style of coaching, regardless of how talented a player is. P\u00e9kerman can make controversial selections with line-ups against certain teams. He experimented heavily with the Argentinean youth squads when he was coaching them.\n\nBefore the 2006 World Cup began, P\u00e9kerman made the controversial decision to drop established defenders [[Javier Zanetti]] and [[Walter Samuel]]. When Argentina was eliminated by Germany in the quarter-finals, his substitution decision caused storms of criticism, as well. Despite the dramatic loss, P\u00e9kerman was still hailed by many fans and press as a very effective coach and the \"P\u00e9kerman Era\" is regarded as one that brought a lot of pride to the country.{{cn|date=July 2018}} His team lost its temper after the elimination and instigated a huge brawl, which was believed to be a major factor in his resignation.\n\n==Managerial statistics==\n:''Statistics accurate as of 12 September 2018''<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://es.fifa.com/fifa-tournaments/players-coaches/people=40510/index.html|title=Torneos FIFA Jugadores y Entrenadores - Jos\u00e9 P\u00c9KERMAN|website=FIFA.com|language=es-ES|access-date=12 October 2017}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.worldfootball.net/teams/kolumbien-team/21/|title=Colombia - Historical results|website=worldfootball.net|language=en-GB|access-date=12 October 2017}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.worldfootball.net/teams/argentinien-team/21/|title=Argentina - Historical results|website=worldfootball.net|language=en-GB|access-date=12 October 2017}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.rsssf.com/tablesa/arg-intres-pekerman.html|title=Argentina - International Matches in Era Pekerman 2004-2006|website=www.rsssf.com|access-date=12 October 2017}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.rsssf.com/tablesa/arg-u23-intres.html|title=U-23 ARGENTINA NATIONAL TEAM - Matches & Statistics 1937-2008|last=Pelayes|first=H\u00e9ctor Dar\u00edo|website=www.rsssf.com|access-date=12 October 2017}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.worldfootball.net/teams/argentinien-u20-h-team/21/|title=Argentina [U20] - Historical results|website=worldfootball.net|language=en-GB|access-date=12 October 2017}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.football-lineups.com/coach/1337/|title=Jose Nestor Pekerman - Football Coach|website=Football-Lineups|language=en|access-date=12 October 2017}}</ref>\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align: center\"\n|-\n!rowspan=\"2\"|Team\n!rowspan=\"2\"|From\n!rowspan=\"2\"|To\n! colspan=\"5\" |Record\n|-\n!P!!W!!D!!L!!Win %\n|-\n|[[Argentina national under-17 football team|Argentina U17]]\n|align=left|May 1995\n|align=left|September 1997\n{{WDL|23|15|3|5}}\n|-\n|[[Argentina national under-20 football team|Argentina U20]]\n|align=left|January 1995\n|align=left|December 2001\n{{WDL|58|42|8|8}}\n|-\n|[[Argentina national under-23 football team|Argentina U23]]\n|align=left|September 1999\n|align=left|February 2000\n{{WDL|15|8|3|4}}\n|-\n|[[Argentina national football team|Argentina]]\n|align=left|October 2004\n|align=left|June 2006\n{{WDL|27|14|7|6}}\n|-\n|[[Deportivo Toluca F.C.|Toluca]]\n|align=left|August 2007\n|align=left|May 2008\n{{WDL|41|18|14|9}}\n|-\n|[[Tigres UANL]]\n|align=left|March 2009\n|align=left|May 2009\n{{WDL|10|1|5|4}}\n|-\n|[[Colombia national football team|Colombia]]\n|align=left|February 2012\n|align=left|August 2018\n{{WDL|77|42|20|15}}\n|-\n!colspan=\"3\"|Total\n{{WDLtot|251|140|60|51}}\n|}\n\n==Personal life==\nP\u00e9kerman was born in [[Villa Dom\u00ednguez]], [[Entre R\u00edos Province|Entre R\u00edos]]. His grandparents immigrated from Ukraine and settled in the Jewish agricultural colonies of [[Entre R\u00edos Province]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.delacole.com/cgi-bin/medios/vernota.cgi?medio=comunidades&numero=396&nota=396-18 |title=JOSE PEKERMAN:UN JUDIO ENTRERIANO &#124; Peri\u00f3dico Jud\u00edo Independiente |publisher=Delacole.com |date=3 September 1949 |accessdate=12 June 2014}}</ref>  P\u00e9kerman is [[Jewish]].<ref>New York Times, [http://kickingscreaming.blogs.nytimes.com/2006/06/27/pekermans-journey/ Pekerman's Journey]. 27 June 2006.</ref>\n\nFollowing Colombia's qualification for the 2014 World Cup, Pekerman stated his desire to be a naturalized Colombian, which was granted by President [[Juan Manuel Santos]] the following day.<ref name=\"comutricolor1\"/>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://fifaworldcup.yahoo.com/06/en/c/team/coach/arg.html Biography] by [[FIFA]]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20010503011339/http://www.geocities.com/Pipeline/Reef/8785/documentoshtm/josepekerman.htm About Pekerman] {{in lang|es}}\n\n{{Navboxes\n|title= Jos\u00e9 Pekerman international tournaments\n|list1=\n{{Navboxes colour\n| title       = Argentina squads\n| bg          = #75aadb\n| fg          = white\n| bordercolor = silver\n| list1       = \n{{Argentina Squad Confederations Cup 2005}}\n{{Argentina squad 2006 FIFA World Cup}}\n}}\n{{Navboxes colour\n| title       = Colombia squads\n|bg=#FCD116\n|fg=#003893\n|bordercolor= #CE1126\n| list1       = \n{{Colombia squad 2014 FIFA World Cup}}\n{{Colombia squad 2015 Copa Am\u00e9rica}}\n{{Colombia squad Copa Am\u00e9rica Centenario}}\n{{Colombia squad 2018 FIFA World Cup}}\n}}\n}}\n{{Navboxes\n| title       = Jos\u00e9 Pekerman managerial positions\n| list1       = \n{{Argentina national football team managers}}\n{{Deportivo Toluca managers}}\n{{Colombia national football team managers}}\n}}\n{{South American Coach of the Year}}\n{{FIFA U-20 World Cup winning managers}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Pekerman, Jose}}\n[[Category:1949 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:People from Entre R\u00edos Province]]\n[[Category:Association football midfielders]]\n[[Category:Argentine footballers]]\n[[Category:Argentinos Juniors footballers]]\n[[Category:Independiente Medell\u00edn footballers]]\n[[Category:Argentine Primera Divisi\u00f3n players]]\n[[Category:Categor\u00eda Primera A players]]\n[[Category:Argentine expatriate footballers]]\n[[Category:Expatriate footballers in Colombia]]\n[[Category:Expatriate football managers in Chile]]\n[[Category:Expatriate football managers in Mexico]]\n[[Category:Argentine expatriate sportspeople in Chile]]\n[[Category:Argentine expatriate sportspeople in Mexico]]\n[[Category:Argentine expatriate sportspeople in Colombia]]\n[[Category:Argentine football managers]]\n[[Category:Argentina national football team managers]]\n[[Category:2005 FIFA Confederations Cup managers]]\n[[Category:2006 FIFA World Cup managers]]\n[[Category:2014 FIFA World Cup managers]]\n[[Category:Deportivo Toluca F.C. managers]]\n[[Category:Tigres UANL managers]]\n[[Category:Colombia national football team managers]]\n[[Category:Argentine Jews]]\n[[Category:Jewish footballers]]\n[[Category:Jewish Argentine sportspeople]]\n[[Category:Argentine people of Ukrainian descent]]\n[[Category:Argentine people of Ukrainian-Jewish descent]]\n[[Category:Argentine emigrants to Colombia]]\n[[Category:2015 Copa Am\u00e9rica managers]]\n[[Category:Copa Am\u00e9rica Centenario managers]]\n[[Category:2018 FIFA World Cup managers]]\n[[Category:Argentine expatriate football managers]]\n", "text_old": "{{spanish name|P\u00e9kerman|Krimen}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=May 2018}}\n{{Infobox football biography\n | name            = Jos\u00e9  P\u00e9kerman\n | image           = Jos\u00e9 N\u00e9stor P\u00e9kerman and Police at Colombia vs Uruguay match for Russia 2018 (cropped).jpg\n | caption         = P\u00e9kerman as [[Colombia national football team|Colombia]] manager in 2016\n | fullname        = Jos\u00e9 N\u00e9stor P\u00e9kerman Krimen<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.ecbloguer.com/capsulas/?p=52627 |title=C\u00e1psulas de f\u00fatbol \u00bb El segundo apellido de Pekerman es Krimen |publisher=Ecbloguer.com |date=22 February 1999 |accessdate=12 June 2014 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140707223843/http://www.ecbloguer.com/capsulas/?p=52627 |archive-date=7 July 2014 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n | height          = 1.76 m\n | birth_date      = {{birth date and age|1949|9|3|df=y}}\n | birth_place     = [[Villa Dom\u00ednguez]], Argentina\n | currentclub     = \n | position        = [[Midfielder]]\n | youthyears1     =            | youthclubs1 = [[Argentinos Juniors]]\n | years1          = 1970\u20131974  | caps1 = 134  | goals1 = 12  | clubs1 = [[Argentinos Juniors]]\n | years2          = 1974\u20131977  | caps2 = 101  | goals2 = 15  | clubs2 = [[Independiente Medell\u00edn]]\n | totalcaps       = 235 | totalgoals = 27\n | manageryears1   = 1981\u20131982  | managerclubs1 = [[Chacarita Juniors]] (youth)\n | manageryears2   = 1982\u20131992  | managerclubs2 = [[Argentinos Juniors]] (youth)\n | manageryears3   = 1992\u20131994  | managerclubs3 = [[Colo-Colo]] (youth)\n | manageryears4   = 1994\u20132001  | managerclubs4 = [[Argentina national under-20 football team|Argentina U20]]\n | manageryears5   = 2004\u20132006  | managerclubs5 = [[Argentina national football team|Argentina]]\n | manageryears6   = 2007\u20132008  | managerclubs6 = [[Club Toluca|Toluca]]\n | manageryears7   = 2009       | managerclubs7 = [[UANL Tigres|Tigres UANL]]\n | manageryears8   = 2012\u20132018  | managerclubs8 = [[Colombia national football team|Colombia]]\n}}\n'''Jos\u00e9 N\u00e9stor P\u00e9kerman Krimen''' ({{IPA-es|xo\u02c8se \u02c8pekerman}}; born 3 September 1949) is an Argentine-Colombian professional [[Association football|football]] coach and former manager of [[Colombia national football team|the Colombian national football team]]. As a youth level coach for Argentina, he won the [[FIFA World Youth Championship]] three times, and the U20 [[South American Youth Championship]] twice. He coached the [[Argentina national football team]] in the [[2006 FIFA World Cup]] and became coach of the [[Colombian national football team|Colombian national team]] in 2012. He subsequently managed the Colombian national team during the 2014 and 2018 FIFA World Cups where he led the team to their best result in 2014.\n\n==Player career==\n[[File:Jos\u00e9 Pekerman Deportivo Toluca 2007.jpg|thumb|Jos\u00e9 P\u00e9kerman in 2007]]\nP\u00e9kerman's career as a footballer was uneventful. A [[midfielder]], he played from 1970 to 1974 for [[Argentinos Juniors]] scoring 12 goals in 134 matches. He was transferred to [[Independiente Medell\u00edn]], in Colombia, where he scored 15 goals in 101 matches.\n\nHis player days ended at age 28 with a serious knee injury. P\u00e9kerman supported himself and his family with various odd jobs, including a stint as a taxi driver.{{CN|date=September 2019}}\n\n==Coaching career==\n===Youth coaching===\nBack in Argentina, P\u00e9kerman worked as a youth coach for [[Chacarita Juniors]] and then occupied the same position with [[Argentinos Juniors]]. He then moved to Chile to coach [[Colo-Colo]]'s youth divisions.\n\nIn 1994, he was offered to coach the Argentina national under-20 and under-17 sides by the [[Argentine Football Association]]. This caused some surprise as his [[r\u00e9sum\u00e9]] did not include any major achievements at this stage. He teamed up with [[Hugo Tocalli]] and coach Eduardo Urtasun.\n\nP\u00e9kerman's success, however, silenced the critics: his under-20 team won the [[FIFA World Youth Championship]] three times, [[1995 FIFA World Youth Championship|1995]] (Qatar), [[1997 FIFA World Youth Championship|1997]] (Malaysia), and [[2001 FIFA World Youth Championship|2001]] (Argentina), thus giving the names to his three pet dogs - Qatar, Malaysia and Argentina. The team also won the two [[South American Youth Championship]]s in 1997 and 1999.\n\nWhen the national coach [[Daniel Passarella]] resigned after the [[1998 FIFA World Cup|1998 World Cup]], P\u00e9kerman was offered his position. He declined, assuming instead the position of general manager of all national teams. [[Marcelo Bielsa]] was hired as coach on P\u00e9kerman's recommendation, and remained in charge until after Argentina's gold medal performance in the 2004 Summer Olympics.\n\nIn 2003, P\u00e9kerman moved to Spain at the behest of Argentine businessman [[Daniel Grinbank]], who had acquired [[Spanish Second Division]] side [[CD Legan\u00e9s]]. After a few months serving as director of football, the project crumbled and P\u00e9kerman left Spain.\n\nWhen Marcelo Bielsa resigned as coach, P\u00e9kerman was one of the two candidates for the coaching job, alongside [[Carlos Bianchi]], who had left [[Boca Juniors]] a few months earlier, and wanted to take a [[sabbatical|sabbatical year]] away from football.\n\n===World Cup 2006===\nOn 15 September 2004, P\u00e9kerman was named coach of the [[Argentina national football team]], which qualified for the [[2006 FIFA World Cup|2006 World Cup]]. The nation dominated its initial two group stage matches and drew with the [[Netherlands national football team|Netherlands]] in the third match, emerging on top of their group on goal difference. The ''Albicelestes'' then moved on to the round of 16, beating [[Mexico national football team|Mexico]] 2\u20131 [[overtime (sports)|after extra time]] in a comeback victory.\n\nIn the quarter-finals, Argentina went ahead 1\u20130 against hosts [[Germany national football team|Germany]], but shortly before the end of the match, Germany equalised through a [[Miroslav Klose]] header. Germany would go on to win on penalties, sending Argentina out of the tournament. P\u00e9kerman made defensive substitutions, including taking off [[Juan Rom\u00e1n Riquelme]] for [[Esteban Cambiasso]], and after the loss, announced his resignation. [[Argentine Football Association]] (AFA) President [[Julio Grondona]] tried to dissuade P\u00e9kerman from leaving, but it was later announced that [[Alfio Basile]], who had previously coached Argentina during the [[1994 FIFA World Cup|1994 World Cup]], would replace him as coach.\n\n===Post-World Cup===\nOn 30 May 2007, P\u00e9kerman resumed his coaching career, taking up the position of head coach of [[Club Toluca]] in Mexico, replacing fellow Argentine [[Am\u00e9rico Gallego]]. At the end of the [[Primera Divisi\u00f3n de M\u00e9xico Clausura 2008|Clausura 2008 tournament]], he was replaced by [[Jos\u00e9 Manuel de la Torre]].\n\nOn 23 February 2009, P\u00e9kerman was appointed as the head coach of [[UANL Tigres]] after the sacking of [[Manuel Lapuente]] following a series of bad results. After the end of [[2009 Primera Divisi\u00f3n de M\u00e9xico Clausura|Clausura 2009]], however, he was terminated and replaced by [[Daniel Guzm\u00e1n]].\n\nIn July 2010, it had been reported that P\u00e9kerman was in serious talks with the [[Australia national association football team|Australian national team]], as well as talks with the [[Japan national football team|Japanese national team]] about taking over the role as senior manager following the resignation of their managers.\n\n===2014 World Cup cycle and becoming coach of Colombia===\nIn January 2012, P\u00e9kerman became the new coach of the [[Colombian national football team|Colombian national team]], replacing ousted coach [[Leonel \u00c1lvarez (footballer, born 1965)|Leonel \u00c1lvarez]]. P\u00e9kerman was the third coach of the Colombian team during the South American World Cup qualifiers; before \u00c1lvarez, [[Hern\u00e1n Dar\u00edo G\u00f3mez]] was at the helm. For his first match, a friendly against Mexico, P\u00e9kerman impressed, with the Colombians completely taking control of the friendly in an eventual 2\u20130 victory. In his first [[2014 FIFA World Cup qualification (CONMEBOL)|qualifying]] match for the [[2014 FIFA World Cup|2014 World Cup]], a struggling Colombia managed to win 0\u20131 over [[Peru national football team|Peru]] in [[Lima]]. P\u00e9kerman, however, was criticized for using a long-range style of play rather than a close midfield passing control. This resulted in a weak Colombian side that lost to [[Ecuador national football team|Ecuador]] 1\u20130 away from home, his first loss.\n\nIn his home debut, P\u00e9kerman orchestrated an astonishing comeback as Colombia demolished [[2011 Copa Am\u00e9rica]] champions [[Uruguay national football team|Uruguay]] 4\u20130 in the seventh round of World Cup qualifiers. Under his direction, Colombia also won 1\u20133 away over [[Chile national football team|Chile]] and 2\u20130 over [[Paraguay national football team|Paraguay]] at home in [[Barranquilla]]. A few days later, P\u00e9kerman experimented without many star players such as [[Radamel Falcao]] and [[James Rodr\u00edguez]] against [[Cameroon national football team|Cameroon]], resulting in a comfortable 3\u20130 home victory. For the last match of 2012, Colombia drew 2014 World Cup hosts [[Brazil national football team|Brazil]] 1\u20131 despite missing two of the squad's star players.\n\nIn the opening match of 2013, P\u00e9kerman experimented yet again, this time against the [[Guatemala national football team|Guatemala]] side; he used only substitutes in a 4\u20131 victory, opting not to deploy senior stars, including Radamel Falcao. During the next round of qualifiers, P\u00e9kerman continued with the promising 4\u20132\u20132\u20132 formation that facilitated Colombia's comfortable defeat of [[Bolivia national football team|Bolivia]] in a 5\u20130 home victory. P\u00e9kerman, however, decided to use a different formation in the match, 4\u20134\u20131\u20131, which led to a shocking 1\u20130 away loss to neighbours [[Venezuela national football team|Venezuela]]. He was heavily criticized for experimenting with his side's formation, a loss that took the nation from second to third place in the qualifying table. In the match against his home nation Argentina, P\u00e9kerman changed the lineup and formation to better \"deal\" with the South American giants, which led to a hard-fought 0\u20130 draw. Despite this, P\u00e9kerman was again questioned with his lineup choices.<ref>{{cite web|author=Featured Columnist |url=http://bleacherreport.com/articles/1666131-argentina-vs-colombia-6-things-we-learned-from-world-cup-qualifer/page/5 |title=Argentina vs. Colombia: 6 Things We Learned from World Cup Qualifier |publisher=Bleacher Report |date=7 June 2013 |accessdate=12 June 2014}}</ref>\n\nAfter Colombia qualified for the 2014 World Cup after a 3\u20133 home draw against Chile, P\u00e9kerman expressed his joy for helping Colombia return to the World Cup for the first time in 16 years, considering it to be \"one of the greatest joys in his life.\"<ref>{{cite web|last=Diego |first=Juan |url=http://comutricolor.com/una-de-las-mayores-alegrias-de-mi-vida-pekerman/ |title=\"Es una de las mayores alegr\u00edas de mi vida\": Jos\u00e9 P\u00e9kerman |publisher=ComuTricolor.com |date= |accessdate=12 June 2014}}</ref> Following Colombia's qualification, P\u00e9kerman received Colombian citizenship from [[Juan Manuel Santos]], the [[president of Colombia]].<ref name=\"comutricolor1\">{{cite web|author=webmaster |url=http://comutricolor.com/jose-pekerman-nacionalidad-colombiana/ |title=Jos\u00e9 P\u00e9kerman ser\u00e1 nacionalizado colombiano |publisher=ComuTricolor.com |date= |accessdate=12 June 2014}}</ref>\n\nColombia won all three of its group matches (scoring nine goals and conceding only two) and went on to defeat Uruguay in the Round of 16 before losing to the host nation of Brazil in the quarter-finals. In August 2014, P\u00e9kerman extended his contract with Colombia until 2018.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.dailymail.co.uk/sport/football/article-2728906/Jose-Pekerman-signs-new-four-year-deal-stay-Colombia-manager.html|title=Pekerman signs new four-year deal to stay on as Colombia manager|work=Mail Online|access-date=12 October 2017}}</ref>\n\nFor the second consecutive time, P\u00e9kerman qualified Colombia for the [[FIFA World Cup]] this time for the [[2018 FIFA World Cup|2018 edition]] in Russia. Colombia suffered a controversial defeat in their first group stage game against a well organized and determined Japan, but then came out much stronger to inflict a 3-0 victory over Poland (effectively knocking them out of the tournament in the process). After beating Senegal 1-0 in the last game of the group stage, Colombia moved to the round of 16 as first in their group. After a bitter and contested match, Colombia lost on penalties to England.\n\n==Honours==\n===Manager===\n;Argentina U20\n*[[South American Youth Championship]]: [[1997 South American U-20 Championship|1997]], [[1999 South American U-20 Championship|1999]]; Runner-up [[1995 South American U-20 Championship|1995]], [[2001 South American U-20 Championship|2001]]\n*[[FIFA U-20 World Cup]]: [[1995 FIFA World Youth Championship|1995]], [[1997 FIFA World Youth Championship|1997]],  [[2001 FIFA World Youth Championship|2001]]\n\n;Argentina\n[[FIFA Confederations Cup]]: Runner-up [[2005 FIFA Confederations Cup|2005]]\n\n===Individual===\n* South American Coach of the Year (3): 2012, 2013, 2014 <ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.losandes.com.ar/notas/2014/1/1/jose-pekerman-mejor-sudamerica-759299.asp |title=Jos\u00e9 Pekerman, el mejor DT de Sudam\u00e9rica - M\u00e1s Deportes - Diario Los Andes |publisher=Losandes.com.ar |date= |accessdate=12 June 2014 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140405004221/http://losandes.com.ar/notas/2014/1/1/jose-pekerman-mejor-sudamerica-759299.asp |archive-date=5 April 2014 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n* IFFHS Best National Coach of the Year Nominee (1): 2013 (5th) <ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.goal.com/en-ke/news/4500/main/2014/01/28/4575364/scolari-named-among-elite-coaches |title=Scolari named among elite coaches |publisher=Goal.com |date=28 January 2014 |accessdate=12 June 2014}}</ref>\n\n==Management style and legacy==\nP\u00e9kerman is known for his tactical management style, often selecting the players that fit his style of coaching, regardless of how talented a player is. P\u00e9kerman can make controversial selections with line-ups against certain teams. He experimented heavily with the Argentinean youth squads when he was coaching them.\n\nBefore the 2006 World Cup began, P\u00e9kerman made the controversial decision to drop established defenders [[Javier Zanetti]] and [[Walter Samuel]]. When Argentina was eliminated by Germany in the quarter-finals, his substitution decision caused storms of criticism, as well. Despite the dramatic loss, P\u00e9kerman was still hailed by many fans and press as a very effective coach and the \"P\u00e9kerman Era\" is regarded as one that brought a lot of pride to the country.{{cn|date=July 2018}} His team lost its temper after the elimination and instigated a huge brawl, which was believed to be a major factor in his resignation.\n\n==Managerial statistics==\n:''Statistics accurate as of 12 September 2018''<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://es.fifa.com/fifa-tournaments/players-coaches/people=40510/index.html|title=Torneos FIFA Jugadores y Entrenadores - Jos\u00e9 P\u00c9KERMAN|website=FIFA.com|language=es-ES|access-date=12 October 2017}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.worldfootball.net/teams/kolumbien-team/21/|title=Colombia - Historical results|website=worldfootball.net|language=en-GB|access-date=12 October 2017}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.worldfootball.net/teams/argentinien-team/21/|title=Argentina - Historical results|website=worldfootball.net|language=en-GB|access-date=12 October 2017}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.rsssf.com/tablesa/arg-intres-pekerman.html|title=Argentina - International Matches in Era Pekerman 2004-2006|website=www.rsssf.com|access-date=12 October 2017}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.rsssf.com/tablesa/arg-u23-intres.html|title=U-23 ARGENTINA NATIONAL TEAM - Matches & Statistics 1937-2008|last=Pelayes|first=H\u00e9ctor Dar\u00edo|website=www.rsssf.com|access-date=12 October 2017}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.worldfootball.net/teams/argentinien-u20-h-team/21/|title=Argentina [U20] - Historical results|website=worldfootball.net|language=en-GB|access-date=12 October 2017}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.football-lineups.com/coach/1337/|title=Jose Nestor Pekerman - Football Coach|website=Football-Lineups|language=en|access-date=12 October 2017}}</ref>\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align: center\"\n|-\n!rowspan=\"2\"|Team\n!rowspan=\"2\"|From\n!rowspan=\"2\"|To\n! colspan=\"5\" |Record\n|-\n!P!!W!!D!!L!!Win %\n|-\n|[[Argentina national under-17 football team|Argentina U17]]\n|align=left|May 1995\n|align=left|September 1997\n{{WDL|23|15|3|5}}\n|-\n|[[Argentina national under-20 football team|Argentina U20]]\n|align=left|January 1995\n|align=left|December 2001\n{{WDL|58|42|8|8}}\n|-\n|[[Argentina national under-23 football team|Argentina U23]]\n|align=left|September 1999\n|align=left|February 2000\n{{WDL|15|8|3|4}}\n|-\n|[[Argentina national football team|Argentina]]\n|align=left|October 2004\n|align=left|June 2006\n{{WDL|27|14|7|6}}\n|-\n|[[Deportivo Toluca F.C.|Toluca]]\n|align=left|August 2007\n|align=left|May 2008\n{{WDL|41|18|14|9}}\n|-\n|[[Tigres UANL]]\n|align=left|March 2009\n|align=left|May 2009\n{{WDL|10|1|5|4}}\n|-\n|[[Colombia national football team|Colombia]]\n|align=left|February 2012\n|align=left|August 2018\n{{WDL|77|42|20|15}}\n|-\n!colspan=\"3\"|Total\n{{WDLtot|251|140|60|51}}\n|}\n\n==Personal life==\nP\u00e9kerman was born in [[Villa Dom\u00ednguez]], [[Entre R\u00edos Province|Entre R\u00edos]]. His grandparents immigrated from Ukraine and settled in the Jewish agricultural colonies of [[Entre R\u00edos Province]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.delacole.com/cgi-bin/medios/vernota.cgi?medio=comunidades&numero=396&nota=396-18 |title=JOSE PEKERMAN:UN JUDIO ENTRERIANO &#124; Peri\u00f3dico Jud\u00edo Independiente |publisher=Delacole.com |date=3 September 1949 |accessdate=12 June 2014}}</ref>  P\u00e9kerman is [[Jewish]].<ref>New York Times, [http://kickingscreaming.blogs.nytimes.com/2006/06/27/pekermans-journey/ Pekerman's Journey]. 27 June 2006.</ref>\n\nFollowing Colombia's qualification for the 2014 World Cup, Pekerman stated his desire to be a naturalized Colombian, which was granted by President [[Juan Manuel Santos]] the following day.<ref name=\"comutricolor1\"/>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://fifaworldcup.yahoo.com/06/en/c/team/coach/arg.html Biography] by [[FIFA]]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20010503011339/http://www.geocities.com/Pipeline/Reef/8785/documentoshtm/josepekerman.htm About Pekerman] {{in lang|es}}\n\n{{Navboxes\n|title= Jos\u00e9 Pekerman international tournaments\n|list1=\n{{Navboxes colour\n| title       = Argentina squads\n| bg          = #75aadb\n| fg          = white\n| bordercolor = silver\n| list1       = \n{{Argentina Squad Confederations Cup 2005}}\n{{Argentina squad 2006 FIFA World Cup}}\n}}\n{{Navboxes colour\n| title       = Colombia squads\n|bg=#FCD116\n|fg=#003893\n|bordercolor= #CE1126\n| list1       = \n{{Colombia squad 2014 FIFA World Cup}}\n{{Colombia squad 2015 Copa Am\u00e9rica}}\n{{Colombia squad Copa Am\u00e9rica Centenario}}\n{{Colombia squad 2018 FIFA World Cup}}\n}}\n}}\n{{Navboxes\n| title       = Jos\u00e9 Pekerman managerial positions\n| list1       = \n{{Argentina national football team managers}}\n{{Deportivo Toluca managers}}\n{{Colombia national football team managers}}\n}}\n{{South American Coach of the Year}}\n{{FIFA U-20 World Cup winning managers}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Pekerman, Jose}}\n[[Category:1949 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:People from Entre R\u00edos Province]]\n[[Category:Association football midfielders]]\n[[Category:Argentine footballers]]\n[[Category:Argentinos Juniors footballers]]\n[[Category:Independiente Medell\u00edn footballers]]\n[[Category:Argentine Primera Divisi\u00f3n players]]\n[[Category:Categor\u00eda Primera A players]]\n[[Category:Argentine expatriate footballers]]\n[[Category:Expatriate footballers in Colombia]]\n[[Category:Expatriate football managers in Chile]]\n[[Category:Expatriate football managers in Mexico]]\n[[Category:Argentine expatriate sportspeople in Chile]]\n[[Category:Argentine expatriate sportspeople in Mexico]]\n[[Category:Argentine expatriate sportspeople in Colombia]]\n[[Category:Argentine football managers]]\n[[Category:Argentina national football team managers]]\n[[Category:2005 FIFA Confederations Cup managers]]\n[[Category:2006 FIFA World Cup managers]]\n[[Category:2014 FIFA World Cup managers]]\n[[Category:Deportivo Toluca F.C. managers]]\n[[Category:Tigres UANL managers]]\n[[Category:Colombia national football team managers]]\n[[Category:Argentine Jews]]\n[[Category:Jewish footballers]]\n[[Category:Jewish Argentine sportspeople]]\n[[Category:Argentine people of Ukrainian descent]]\n[[Category:Argentine people of Ukrainian-Jewish descent]]\n[[Category:Argentine emigrants to Colombia]]\n[[Category:2015 Copa Am\u00e9rica managers]]\n[[Category:Copa Am\u00e9rica Centenario managers]]\n[[Category:2018 FIFA World Cup managers]]\n[[Category:Argentine expatriate football managers]]\n", "name_user": "208.180.184.130", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Jos%C3%A9_P%C3%A9kerman"}
